deck_excerpt: Vampire Zombie World with the new support + combo guide
deck_description:
Intro: As you may know, zombies got some new synchros recently. 1 of them is a zombie synchro tuner that does a free foolish burial??? that one is insane, the others are "kinda mid tbh". So I did some experimenting and I found that with vampires and zombie world you can summon all three of these synchros on your opponent's turn if you really wanted to. I however decided that those synchros just aren't worth the extra deck space or the effort to summon them. If you want to use them go ahead, but I personally will just take Baroness De Fleur and call it a week. As always I don't list any 3 card combos, I leave those to the player to figure those out. ====================================================================================================================================================================================== Deck: (9 Cards) Combo Starters: (3x) Shiranui Solitare (3x) Uni-Zombie (3x) Vampire Ghost Ogre   (16 Cards) Combo Extenders/Pieces: (1x) Vampire Scarlet Scourge (1x) Vampire Grace (1x) Shadow Vampire (2x) Necroworld Banshee (2x) Mezuki (3x) Vampire Familiar (3x) Vampire Retainer (1x) Foolish Burial (1x) Vampire Domain (1x) Vampire's Desire   (2 cards) Bricks: (1x) Doomking Balerdroch (1x) Glow-up Bloom   (3 Cards) Core Cards (1x) Vampire Domination (2x) Zombie World   (10 Cards) Tech Cards: (2x) Super Polymerization (2x) Called by the Grave (2x) Crossout Designator (2x) Infinite Impermanence (2x) Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring ====================================================================================================================================================================================== Vampire Ghost Ogre + Vampire Familiar/Retainer:
  1. Normal Summon Vampire Ghost Ogre and Activate its effect
  2. Send Vampire Familiar/Retainer from hand to grave and search out Vampire Grace
  3. Send Vampire Retainer/Familiar from deck to grave with Vampire Ghost Ogre's effect
  4. Activate Vampire Familiar in grave and discard Vampire Grace to search out Shadow Vampire
  5. Activate Vampire Retainer in Grave and send Vampire Ghost Ogre from the field to the grave to search out Vampire Domination
  6. Link Vampire Sucker
  7. Activate Vampire Ghost Ogre in grave to normal summon Shadow Vampire, Tributing Vampire Sucker
  8. Activate Shadow Vampire on summon to special summon Vampire Scarlet Scourge
  9. Chain Link 1: Activate Vampire Grace in Grave to special summon itself.
  10. Chain Link 2: Activate Vampire Scarlet Scourge on summon to special summon vampire sucker from the grave
  11. Draw 1 Card with Vampire Sucker
  12. XYZ summon into Beatrice Lady of the Eternal
  13. Activate Beatrice's effect to send Necroworld Banshee from deck to grave
  14. Banish Necroworld Banshee in grave to play Zombie World from the deck
  15. Set Vampire Domination and whatever other backrow you want and pass turn
  16. During your opponent's Draw Phase, activate Beatrice's effect to send Doomking Balerdroch from deck to grave.
  17. During your opponent's Standby Phase, Activate Doomking Balerdroch's effect in grave to special summon itself
  18. (Optional: Activate Grace in grave to special summon itself)
  19. Draw 1 Card with Vampire Sucker
This Combo should leave you with 5 Cards in your hand, assuming you didn't set any extra back row. Vampire Ghost Ogre + Any Vampire Card: 
  1. Normal Summon Vampire Ghost Ogre and Activate its effect
  2. Send Vampire Card from hand to grave and search out Vampire Grace
  3. Send Vampire Familiar from deck to grave with Vampire Ghost Ogre's effect
  4. Activate Vampire Familiar in grave and discard Vampire Grace to search out Shadow Vampire
  5. Link Vampire Sucker
  6. Activate Vampire Ghost Ogre in grave to normal summon Shadow Vampire, Tributing Vampire Sucker
  7. Activate Shadow Vampire on summon to special summon Vampire Scarlet Scourge
  8. Chain Link 1: Activate Vampire Grace in Grave to special summon itself.
  9. Chain Link 2: Activate Vampire Scarlet Scourge on summon to special summon vampire sucker from the grave
  10. Draw 1 Card with Vampire Sucker
  11. XYZ summon into Beatrice Lady of the Eternal
  12. Activate Beatrice's effect to send Necroworld Banshee from deck to grave
  13. Banish Necroworld Banshee in grave to play Zombie World from the deck
  14. whatever other backrow you want and pass turn
  15. During your opponent's Draw Phase, activate Beatrice's effect to send Doomking Balerdroch from deck to grave.
  16. During your opponent's Standby Phase, Activate Doomking Balerdroch's effect in grave to special summon itself
  17. (Optional: Activate Grace in grave to special summon itself)
  18. Draw 1 Card with Vampire Sucker
This Combo should leave you with 5 Cards in your hand, assuming you didn't set any extra back row. Shiranui Solitare/Uni-Zombie + Vampire Ghost Ogre:
  1. Normal Summon Shiranui Solitare
  2. Tribute Shiranui Solitare to special summon Uni-Zombie from the deck
  3. Activate Uni-Zombie to send Vampire Familiar from deck to grave
(If you have Domain: Activate Vampire Domain on field and pay 500 LP for an extra normal summon)
  1. Activate Vampire Familiar in grave sending Vampire Ghost Ogre/Vampire Domain from deck to grave and special summon itself
  2. Activate Vampire Familiar on summon to search out Shadow Vampire
  3. Tribute summon Shadow Vampire using Vampire Familiar
(If you have Ghost Ogre: Activate Ghost Ogre in Grave for an extra normal summon)
  1. Activate Shadow Vampire to special summon Vampire Retainer from the deck
  2. Activate Vampire Retainer to search out Vampire's Desire
  3. Synchro Summon into Immortal Dragon
  4. Activate Immortal Dragon's effect to mill Mezuki
  5. Activate Vampire Desire, Targetting Shadow Vampire, and send Vampire Grace from deck to grave
  6. Link Summon into Crystron Halqifibrax and activate its effect to special summon Glow-up Bloom from the deck
  7. Activate Mezuki in Grave to special summon immortal dragon
  8. Activate Vampire Grace in grave to special summon itself
  9. XYZ summon into Beatrice Lady of the Eternal
  10. Activate Beatrice's effect to send Necroworld Banshee from deck to grave
  11. Banish Necroworld Banshee in grave to play Zombie World from the deck
  12. Link summon into Linkuriboh and special summon Doomking Balerdroch from your deck using glow-up bloom's effect in grave
  13. Link Summon into Vampire Sucker using Doomking baledroch and linkuriboh
  14. Set whatever backrow you want
  15. On your opponent's draw phase, activate Beaatrice Lady of the Eternal to send the 2nd Necroworld Banshee from deck to grave
  16. During your opponent's standby phase, Activate Doomking Balerdroch's effect in grave to special summon itself
  17. (Optional: Activate Grace in grave to special summon itself)
  18. Draw 1 Card with Vampire Sucker
  19. When you want to banish a monster from field or grave on your opponent's turn, activate Crystron Halqifibrax's effect to summon Formula Synchron and draw 1 card (if Chain Link 1)
  20. Chain Doomking's effect to Halqifibrax's effect to banish a card on the field
  21. Once You have exhausted Doomking's effects, Activate Formula Synchron's effect to synchro summon into Baronne De Fleur.
This combo should leave you with 4 cards in your hand, assuming you didn't set any extra back row. Shiranui Solitare/Uni-Zombie + Vampire Familiar:
  1. Normal Summon Shiranui Solitare
  2. Tribute Shiranui Solitare to special summon Uni-Zombie from the deck
  3. Activate Uni-Zombie to send Vampire Retainer from deck to grave
  4. Activate Vampire Retainer and send Vampire familiar to the grave to special summon itself
  5. Activate retainer's effect on summon to search out vampire domain
  6. activate vampire domain and pay 500 lp for an extra normal summon
  7. activate familiar's effect and send vampire domain to the grave to special summon itself
  8. Activate Vampire familiar's effect to search out Shadow Vampire
  9. Normal summon shadow vampire tribuing vampire familiar and activate shadow vampire's effect on summon
  10. Special summon vampire grace from your deck
  11. Synchro summon into Immortal Dragon
  12. Activate Immortal dragon to send mezuki from deck to grave
  13. Link summon into crystron halqifibrax using Immortal Dragon and Vampire Grace, and special summon glow-up bloom from the deck
  14. activate Mezuki in grave to special summon Immortal Dragon
  15. Activate vampire grace in grave to special summon itself
  16. XYZ summon into Beatrice Lady of the Eternal
  17. Activate Beatrice's effect to send Necroworld Banshee from deck to grave
  18. Banish Necroworld Banshee in grave to play Zombie World from the deck
  19. Synchro summon into stardust Charge Warrior, and activate glow-up bloom's effect in grave to special summon Doomking from the deck.
  20. Activate Charge Warrior's effect to draw 1 card.
  21. Link summon with Charge Warrior and Doomking to make Vampire Sucker.
  22. During your opponent's Draw Phase, Send your 2nd Necroworld Banshee from deck to grave
  23. During your opponent's standby phase, Activate Doomking Balerdroch's effect in grave to special summon itself
  24. (Optional: Activate Grace in grave to special summon itself)
  25. Draw 1 Card with Vampire Sucker
  26. When you want to banish a monster from field or grave on your opponent's turn, activate Crystron Halqifibrax's effect to summon Formula Synchron and draw 1 card (if Chain Link 1)
  27. Chain Doomking's effect to Halqifibrax's effect to banish a card on the field
  28. Once You have exhausted Doomking's effects, Activate Formula Synchron's effect to synchro summon in to Baronne De Fleur.
This combo should leave you with 5 cards in your hand, assuming you didn't set any extra back row Shiranui Solitare/Uni-Zombie + Vampire Retainer:
  1. Normal Summon Shiranui Solitare
  2. Tribute Shiranui Solitare to special summon Uni-Zombie from the deck
  3. Activate Uni-Zombie to send Vampire Familiar from deck to grave
  4. Activate Vampire Familiar and send Vampire Retainer from deck to grave to special summon itself
  5. Activate Vampire Familiar's effect on summon to search out vampire Grace
  6. Activate Vampire Retainer's effect and send Vampire Grace to the grave to special summon itself
  7. Activate Vampire Retainer's effect on summon to search out Vampire Domination
  8. Synchro summon into Immortal Dragon
  9. activate immortal dragon to send mezuki from the deck to the grave
  10. Link summon into crystron halqifibrax and special summon glow-up bloom from the deck
  11. Activate Mezuki in the grave to special summon immortal dragon
  12. activate Vampire Grace in the grave to special summon itself
  13. XYZ summon into Beatrice Lady of the Eternal
  14. Activate Beatrice's effect to send Necroworld Banshee from deck to grave
  15. Banish Necroworld Banshee in grave to play Zombie World from the deck
  16. Link summon into Linkuriboh and special summon Doomking Balerdroch from your deck using glow-up bloom's effect in grave
  17. Link Summon into Vampire Sucker using Doomking baledroch and linkuriboh
  18. Set Vampire Domination and whatever backrow you want
  19. During your opponent's Draw Phase, Send your 2nd Necroworld Banshee from deck to grave
  20. During your opponent's standby phase, Activate Doomking Balerdroch's effect in grave to special summon itself
  21. (Optional: Activate Grace in grave to special summon itself)
  22. Draw 1 Card with Vampire Sucker
  23. When you want to banish a monster from field or grave on your opponent's turn, activate Crystron Halqifibrax's effect to summon Formula Synchron and draw 1 card (if Chain Link 1)
  24. Chain Doomking's effect to Halqifibrax's effect to banish a card on the field
  25. Once You have exhausted Doomking's effects, Activate Formula Synchron's effect to synchro summon in to Baronne De Fleur.
This combo should leave you with 4 cards in your hand, assuming you didn't set any extra back row Shiranui Solitare/Uni-Zombie + Mezuki/Necroworld Banshee
  1. Normal Summon Shiranui Solitare
  2. Tribute Shiranui Solitare to special summon Uni-Zombie from the deck
  3. Activate Uni-Zombie's effect and send Necroworld Banshee/Mezuki from deck to grave
  4. Activate Uni-Zombie's effect and discard Mezuki/Necroworld Banshee
  5. Activate Mezuki in grave to special summon Necroworld Banshee from your grave
  6. Link Summon into Crystron Halqifibrax and special summon glow-up bloom from your deck
  7. Activate Necroworld Banshee in your grave to activate Zombie World from your deck
  8. Link summon into linkuriboh and activate glow-up bloom in your grave to play doomking from your deck
  9. Link summon into Vampire Sucker using Doomking and Linkuriboh
  10. Set any extra back row
  11. During your opponent's standby phase, Activate Doomking Balerdroch's effect in grave to special summon itself
  12. Draw 1 Card with Vampire Sucker
  13. When you want to banish a monster from field or grave on your opponent's turn, activate Crystron Halqifibrax's effect to summon Formula Synchron and draw 1 card (if Chain Link 1)
  14. Chain Doomking's effect to Halqifibrax's effect to banish a card on the field
  15. Once You have exhausted Doomking's effects, Activate Formula Synchron's effect to synchro summon in to Baronne De Fleur.
This combo should leave you with 4 cards in your hand, assuming you didn't set any extra back row ====================================================================================================================================================================================== Notes: -This deck is cyberbullied so badly by hand traps that they will literally never be meta. 9 times out of 10 you just hope to either open with crossout designator/called by the grave or your opponent has no hand traps. I wouldn't recommend playing this against a deck that plays a lot of hand traps/counter traps since there is only so much you can do to stop them -If your wondering how to summon all the other new synchros with this deck, it mostly involves using formula synchron 3 times on your opponent's turn. Jack-O-Bolan/Hela and the level 10 synchro both can do that pretty easily, I don't do it cuz its a lot of extra deck space and only rlly performed through with 1 combo. -If you have a level 5 or higher in your hand and Vampire Sucker on the field, try not to forget you can tribute your opponent's monsters for a tribute summon (while you have zombie world). If you can get Vampire Ghost Ogre in Grave you can do it on your opponent's turn. -Swapping to TCG rules is easy, just remove 1 called by the grave and add 1 Crossout Designator ====================================================================================================================================================================================== Conclusion: I originally made this deck to keep up with my friends playing super strong meta decks and super strong combo decks. What ended up happening however is I found myself preferring to play Vampires with Vampire Kingdom over zombie world. That said,  Zombie World is definitely better and my friend plays eldlich so don't take my advice on which to play. The side deck is kinda thrown together, not much thought in it. I'm open to any advice, if you have an idea you should post it so others know too. Leave a like if you enjoyed the deck, and thanks for reading.

deck_excerpt: A deck that encourages blind ashing Small World :)
deck_description: I found that no one ever ashes Small World, so I wanted to make a deck that heavily punishes your opponent for doing that by adding Lava Golem. Honestly a welcome consistency card for getting to network as well since Lava Golem and Numeron Wall are both Fiends. There aren't many monsters in the deck so the lines of what gets to what are pretty simple.  Reveal Wall ----> Ash ----> Lava Golem and vice versa  Reveal Gadarla ----> Lava Golem ----> Vanity's Ruler or Ash or Wall  I am main decking Vanity's Ruler and Solemn Judgment because there's enough blowout cards to deal with basically any deck, so you have the room to just play going 1st cards as well in case someone figures out your strategy and thinks they can make you start. You don't need to do this, you can just play even more going 2nd cards if you wish.  As for the extra deck, I'd say the only cards you care about are the numerons obviously, the Apollousa, the Saryuja, and the Megaclops. Cards like Goddess seem good and can catch your opponent off guard, but Borrelcode and Zeroboros could be anything else that you prefer.  In the side, the only card of note is probably Link Bound, I found this card to be good at clearing monsters off of your field so you can activate network while also recycling a monster and potentially fixing your hand. You probably only ever want to see this card going 1st so that's why it's in the side.

deck_excerpt: The objective is to show 28 possible combos in the deck which for me is the most fun way to play Dino
deck_description: Comments about the decklist: I've always been used to using a very small Dino engine and I refuse to use more than 40 cards, I would like to be using at least one more Lost World and Petiteranodon which brings more versatility in using Pankratops but for now the Dino engine is ok. You don't need 3 Baby in this deck if you play correctly most of the time it won't be missed, some of the combos you can do with just one Babycerasarus. Archosaur has never required more than one copy in the deck and in this version even less, you only need to resolve Archosaur once in the game and I prefer to have Oviraptor and Scrap Raptor as Normal Summons. And speaking of Scrap engine you only need two Scrap Raptor and Chimera in the main deck, as I show in combos you can do full combo using only one Scrap Raptor. Regarding the Ogdoadic engine what I see most people asking is why I use Aron instead of other better Ogdoadic cards and I know why they think Aron is bad because they play Ogdoadic and in the pure version strategy there are bosses much better monsters but in this version Aron fills the needs I need like the 5th name of Ogdoadic. The extra deck I wouldn't change anything, each card helps me a lot, of course I would like to have room for more versatility cards like Lambda or Castel but for now I don't miss it. The Side deck are just examples of good cards for you to dig and play in GY with the Chaos Ruler effect, it's not a real side deck although I think it's very good to test Mind Control and Bigfoot! mainly for being lv8, having 3k atk that takes a Dragoon for example and having the possibility to take out floodgates like Imperial Order and Anti-Spell. Finally, on the gameplay of why the deck is interesting: Turn 1 you usually spend with what Dino does best which is Tyranno + Dolkka and what Ogdoadic does best which is a Rank8 but what makes this deck oppressor are the follow ups, on the way back you have the Scrap engine threatening Borreload Savage, you can have Chaos Ruler in the GY that along with the Ogdoadic engine threatens Dingirsu, you also easily threaten to do Exciton Knight, there's Misc + Rex that threaten Tyranno / Pankratops + a Rank4 which is giant in the grind game. So you generate so much advantage in GY that it's no use your opponent breaking your field, he'll have to OTK because otherwise your turn is scary. This is not the new secret deck that destroys the meta but I believe it is the best way to still play Dino besides being fun and requiring considerable skill because it is not linear, each combo I present can be done differently depending on from gamestate, there are times when you can connect only the Ogdoadic engine and the Dino engine is like Follow Up waiting for a draw to debrick or the other way around.  Below are all the combos I learned from this deck: The basic deck combo is from the standard Scrap Dino moves like Oviraptor + Baby = Misc + Baby = Archosaur + Baby = Oviraptor + Misc I hope you can understand the plays I made because some of these replays are not in a didactic way because they are more test hands that I do randomly mainly in the Scrap part which has more details of the cards I destroyed for each effect that activates or times I add the Double Evolution Pill to my hand out of the blue because I forgot to add it when using Archosaur, which are things you forget when training in a manual simulator. I like to use the expression Cyber Punk 2077 when I find a really good combo that nobody does with the deck and you'll see I have some of them on this list.  Place the URL continuation on the duelingbook site after .com/  replay?id=621416-34750463 Oviraptor + Babycerasaurus Dinosaur Ogdoadic Combo ROUTE of Chaos Ruler excavate Nunu = Tyranno + Dolkka + Wyvern + Giant Rex + Number 38 or Dingirsu. Using Chaos Ruler to access the Scrap engine is possible but it depends on luck if you can add Nunu or Nauya to your hand which I don't recommend. Play Around Lightning Storm. Don't play Around Super Poly if you make Number 38.  replay?id=813757-33319802 Oviraptor + Babycerasaurus Dinosaur Ogdoadic Combo King of the Feral Imps ROUTE = Tyranno + Dolkka + Wyvern + Giant Rex + Number 38 or Dingirsu  replay?id=813757-33348537 Deck Full Combo - the apex using Chaos Ruler (not playing around hand trap) doing Evolzar Dolkka only in the middle of the combo = Tyranno + Dolkka + I:P + Number 97 and Number 38 + Possible Gamma in Hand that you can add with Chaos Ruler. I was still using the Number 97 engine in this replay but nowadays I see that the Rank 8 Toolbox I use today is much better. I thought the idea presented in this combo was cool so I'm including it too.  replay?id=813757-33376148 Version 2 of the deck's Full Combo = Tyranno + Dolkka + Savage + Number 38  replay?id=813757-33376688 Full Combo Version 3 = Tyranno + Dolkka + Wyvern + Number 38 /in GY: Chaos Ruler and Misc and Rex and Ogdoadic monsters /in Hand: monster that you added with Chaos Ruler.  replay?id=813757-33373914 Lost World + Scrap Raptor (Don't Play Around Hand Traps) = Tyranno + Dolkka + Wyvern + Linkuriboh + Number 38 or 68 or Dingirsu (In this combo Oviraptor destroys the Token in the opponent's field to reborn Babycerasaurus but the DB won't let me destroy it, just to be clear)  replay?id=813757-33348273 Full Combo with 1 Scrap Raptor and playing around Hand Trap = Tyranno + Dolkka + Wyvern + Giant Rex + Number 38 or Dingirsu and Scrap Raptor in Hand  replay?id=813757-33374185 Full Combo Cyber ​​Punk 2077 with 1 Scrap Raptor (Don't Playing Around Hand Traps) = Tyranno + Dolkka + Wyvern + Chimera + Number 38 or 68 or Dingirsu (It's Combo Cyber ​​Punk 2077 because your Ultimate Conductor Tyranno is not just Book of Eclipse but a pop without targeting additionally because you destroy Scrap Chimera and Scrap Wyvern's eff trigger to give summon from Scrap Raptor that we still have in the deck to pop a card without targeting, that way you don't need to use Tyranno's effect so early in the combo)  replay?id=813757-33348803 Lost World + Oviraptor (Use Chaos Ruler) = Tyranno + Wyvern + (Number 97 or Number 38 or Number 68) /in Hand: Possible Gamma added with Chaos Ruler /in GY: Misc in GY + Chaos Ruler Or replay?id=813757-33480783 Lost World + Oviraptor (Chaos Ruler ROTA) = Tyranno + Masquerena I:P + Number 38 /in Hand: Add of Chaos Ruler /in GY: Misc + Chaos Ruler follow up + half of the Ogdoadic names  replay?id=813757-33374505 Cyber ​​Punk Combo 2077 Oviraptor + Miscellaneousaurus Blind Second = Exciton Knight + Number 38 or Number 68 + Misc in GY (It's not hard to make Exciton Knight with the Ogdoadic engine too) Or replay?id=813757-34766275 Cyber ​​Punk Combo 2077 Lost World + Oviraptor Blind Second = Exciton Knight + Tyranno + Pankratops + Wyvern + Chimera  replay?id=813757-33374781 Lost World + Babycerasaurus Blind Second combo (Play Around Hand Traps) = Tyranno + Dolkka + Wyvern + Giant Rex + Number 38 or 68 or Dingirsu  replay?id=813757-33335815 Nauya + anymonster = Number 97 or Number 38 or Number 68 /in GY: 4 more important of the Ogdoadic names This is good if for example you give NS Ovirapor and the opponent denies it to extend moves and pass with something that guarantees you to survive.  replay?id=813757-33334708 Nunu + any Level4 Dinosaur = Number 38 or Number 68 + Ogdoadic Spell/Trap  replay?id=813757-33335402 Nunu + anyLv4Dino = I:P Masq + Aron, the Ogdoadic King  replay?id=813757-33333176 Snake Rain + Discard = Number 97 + Number 38 or Number 68 and Ogdoadic Spell/Trap in Hand  replay?id=813757-33336243 Snake Rain + Discard = I:P Masq + Aron, the Ogdoadic King  replay?id=813757-33337033 Archosaur + Giant Rex (any Dino Lv4) = Rank 8  replay?id=813757-33364312 Oviraptor + Double Evolution Pill = Tyranno + Rank 8 (better to make Number 97 and Number 38) /in GY: Miscellaneousaurus + Top 4 Ogdoadic names  Scrap Raptor = Rank 4 (Bagooska) or Rank 8  replay?id=813757-33379833 Oviraptor + Baby + Nunu Combo with the Chaos Ruler ROUTE = Tyranno + I:P Masquerena + Aron + Number 38 /in Hand: Possible monster added with Chaos Ruler eff /in GY: Misc + all the Ogdoadic Names (At the end of the combo it was strange that I summoned Nauya from the deck but actually I made a mistake because I was supposed to send Aron straight to GY and then summon the resolution and this Nauya was supposed to be in the Deck)  replay?id=813757-33379559 Oviraptor + Baby + Nunu Combo with the Borreload Savage ROUTE = Tyranno + I:P Masquerena + Borreload Savage + Rank 8 /in Hand: Possible monster added with Chaos Ruler eff /in GY: Misc + half of the Ogdoadic names (In this combo I Missplayed not to destroy the King of the Feral Imps after the summon of the second Scrap Raptor so I had an extra body on the table and I could do I:P Masquerena. I ask you to redo this combo because most likely this one I:P should not be on the final board, the rest of the monsters remain the same but there may be some significant change in the Ogdoadic activation sequence lv8)  replay?id=813757-33433361 Oviraptor + Baby + Nauya Combo with Chaos Ruler ROUTE = Tyranno + Dolkka + Wyvern + Masquerena I:P + Number 38  replay?id=813757-33433724 Ovirapor + Baby + Nauya Combo with Borreload Savage ROUTE = Tyranno + Dolkka + Borreload Savage + Number 38  replay?id=813757-33434633 Scrap Raptor + Miscellaneousaurus Combo King of the Feral Imps ROUTE works = Tyranno + I:P Masquerena + Aleirtt /in GY: 3 Ogdoadic names + Misc (The second test hand with the Chaos Ruler ROUTE shows why it's a risky play, you may just not be able to dig out any Ogdoadic names and have the entire combo hurt)  replay?id=813757-33380488 Snake Rain + Scrap Raptor = Masquerena I:P + Bagooska /in GY: Chaos Ruler + all the Ogdoadic names /in Hand: Search of Chaos Ruler (The first time I had summoned from Aron because of the autopilot but you must summon from Nauya to access Bagooska)  replay?id=813757-33382243 Snake Rain + Oviraptor the 3 possible situations: First: Archosaur add Double Evolution Pill and make Linkuriboh + I:P Masquerena /in Hand: Double Evolution Pill + Ogdoadic Spell/Trap (discard of Knightmare Unicorn) /in GY: Misc + 3 ogdoadic names Second: add Misc and let him down and pass with I:P Masquerena + Aron + an Ogdoadic Monster in the Hand (discard of Knightmare Unicorn) + Misc. (I was undecided about activating the spell Water Lily or the Nauya effect and after that I saw that it makes a lot more sense to use Spell in this case) Third: Use Archosaur to add an Ogdoadic name and pass with I:P + Bagooska /in GY: Misc and all the Ogdoadic names. This combo is also possible if the Snake Rain dropout is a Reptile so you can add the Pill straight to the hand which is much better.  replay?id=813757-34766606 what do you do if you draw one of the bricks(Keurse or Aleirtt)? Simple, do the combo normally and at the end do Unicorn and use the eff to shuffle himself back to the extra deck and that way you can discard the Brick to the GY. This was a move that Adamancipator with Block Dragon did a lot, but in their case it wasn't to take a Brick from the deck, but to open space on the field to give summons from Block Dragon. (In this combo I should have sent Nunu to GY instead of Aron because that way the Ogdoadic engine would be complete with the top 4 names in circulation)

deck_name: Nekroz Dogmatika Post BOCH (Battle Of Chaos)
deck_excerpt: Nekroz Dogmatika Post BOCH can certainly contend in a combo heavy format that ends on Extra Deck monsters to attempt to control the game.
deck_description: This is a deck that providing it gets the right banlist and the meta is ED reliant, can thrive. You can still manage backrow decks with the likes of Denko but your G1 is severely hindered by them so if you wanted to play it in a backrow heavy environment, Denko should be considered in the main over something like Chalice or Droplet. List is definitely cuttable to a straight 40 if you wanted to go this route as you could replace one of the monster negates in the main with Harpie's Feather Duster instead for example. If you wish to play the list in the current format, just cut White Exalted of Dogmatika and Dogmatikabre and the deck will function almost the same but with slightly less power. Nadir Servant being able to send Herald Of The Arc Light to search either of the Dogamtika Rituals and then benefit the Nekroz monsters with the search from Herald Of The Arc Light is really nice as well as Dogmatikalamity being able to send Herald Of The Arc Light in order to summon White Exalted of Dogmatika in the same way that Nekroz Kaleidoscope is another feature that is nice to have whilst also boosting the attack of something such as Nekroz of Unicore in order to make it more difficult to attack over in the process.     Unfortunately, the deck does lose really hard to Droll & Lock Bird but thankfully with the decline in popularity of Drytron in the current meta, Droll & Lock Bird is being switched out for some other handtraps outside of combo decks that can use it and then proceed to put big bodies on the board and attempt to OTK you. I would do a combos section but your main thing is that you play whichever engine you draw while trying to get yourself to the other half of deck in the process through the use of Nadir Servant, Dogmatikalamity and Nekroz Kaleidoscope. Any other questions please feel free to ask. I do by no means think that this deck will be Tier 1, but it will certainly be able to deal with them in a Rouge capacity.

deck_excerpt: Cyberdark deck that seeks to build Cyberdarkness Dragon and Cyberdark End Dragon as the main boss monsters.
deck_description: The deck's goal is to make Cyberdarkness Dragon, and either stay on it for the negates, or move to Cyberdark End Dragon if your opponent doesn't have an answer to it. How we get there is pretty typical for cyberdark decks: use Cannon and Claw to search creatures and spells, respectively, with the goal of filling up the graveyard and hand with at least 5 cyberdark monsters. Use chimera to search for Power Bond, and fuse your boss monster. We have two Power Bonds, in case we open with one, and we're running one Attachment Cybern and three Cyberdark Invasion to allow Cyberdarkness dragon to have more negates.  If our boss monsters are destroyed, we can recurse them with Cyber Eternal, which we can search with Cyber Dragon Core. Our main source of removal is attacking, but we can also use Jizukiru to tribute an opponents monster, then fuse him with our Cyber Dragon Core to make Chimeratech Fortress Dragon.  In the extra deck, Heavy Armored Train Ironwolf is there in case we can't make it to full combo.  One of the deck's big weak spots is its inability to draw. If we make our boss monsters and they are removed, we need cards in hand to make followup plays, so try to conserve your hand as best as possible.

deck_excerpt: A competitive deck using the D/D/D archetype
deck_description:
There's really only one combo that I know well with this deck. D/D/D DIMENSION SUMMON
  1. Hold out for your hand to have the following cards: Swirl Slime, Nighthowl, 1 Lvl7 D/D/D, 1 D/D/D (DIFFERENT THAN THE Lvl7)
  2. Activate Swirl Slime from the hand, and fusion summon Dragonbane King Beowulf using itself and your Lvl7 D/D/D
  3. Activate Swirl Slime in the GY, and special summon the other D/D/D in your hand.
  4. Normal Summon Nighthowl and use its effect to summon the Lvl7 D/D/D From your graveyard
  5. Synchro Summon High Gust King Alexander
Now, you should have Dragonbane King Beowulf, a random D/D/D monster, and High Gust King Alexander with 6000 Atk on the field. If your opponent has counter cards, then you can always wait for the card you need to be drawn again. You can also perform a similar combo using D/D Berfomet, using its effect to change Nighthowl to Lvl6. Also, it doesn't have to be Gust High King Alexander for this combo, it could be a different synchro. Feel free to experiment with different cards to make the most effective combo.

deck_excerpt: A fun yet effective way of using Resonators and Red Dragon Archfiends to swarm the field, control the board and achieve massive combos that bring out
deck_description: Basically you combo out Red Rising Dragon using your lvl 2 resonators and your lvl 4 dark monsters. Then, use Red Rising's effect to special summon the lvl 2 tuner you used. If it's red resonator you can gain 2100 lp and go into Scarlet Red Dragon and if it's crimson resonator you can bring out two resonators from your deck (like red resonator and synkron resonator) which you can use to go into other boss monsters like Hot Red Dragon, Tyrant Red Dragon, King Calamity or even Red Supernova. Allure, Resonator Call, Resonator Command, Witch of the Black Forest and Synkron Resonator all help get cards needed to start combos and extend combos. The Synchro boss monsters (lvl 9+) also protect themselves and other monsters with their negates or swarm the field with resonators or lower level Synchro monster so you can go into bigger Synchro monsters. This deck is a first turn deck but can also work on second turn if you opponent doesn't have facedowns.

deck_excerpt: A WCS contendor truly worthy of merit in its own way.
deck_description:
Video is out now. Sorry it's been awhile....

(https://youtu.be/jnWfuCNJ7R8) So it has been awhile since I made a decently put together deck that is just as generic as my confidence for life. Anywho, because WCS season is around, and we all know it will be a blood bath that makes 2008 look like someone knocked over a bottle of water; let me clarify that I think Lyrilusc - Tri-Brigade will hold out the longest of all the current decks running around before then. However doesn't mean that Lyrilusc can hold their own with or without the entity of the Tri-Brigade. This time it is not Fraktall that is leading the charge at all. Sure he can mill, be Kit's side posse, and hold on better than Kerass; but in reality, Nervall is the one doing the important work by searching out the needed Birds for the plays that truly matter. On the note of how the lyrilusc monsters can be useful here, let's say that I'm glad to have Crossout Designator in this deck. The reason in this case is because Special Summoning is your best friend on all fronts; from XYZ summoning, to Link Summoning, to even GY setup. What this gets you is the Utopic Future package. A very obscure package that brings you "Number F0: Utopic Draco Future": an XYZ monster that negates and steals monsters from your opponent to use them however you want to. Other than that nothing has basically changed out of this aspiring hybrid that has so many chances of making a truly versatile impact.

deck_description: You can usually build 2 types of BLS decks: Decks that use Envoy of the Beginning in a Light/Dark themed deck or Bad Decks.  This Archetype is starving for decent support. No the Gaias don't count, I have desperatly tried to make them work, it ends in pain. No the new Fusion dosen't count either, That one was made for Dark Magician.  You could probably improve the deck (especially the extra deck) a bit more but this is what im rolling with mainly cuz i don't know any other good cards and also laziness.  Just get the Field Spell, Slam that sucker down, go for isolde, get Super Soldier Soul, send his ass to the GY, pop his GY effect to yoink a beginning or evening knight out of the deep dark pits of your deck, use the tokens on the Field Spell and then get the boi out there! Jarngreipr is there for protection if you are either going first, have 2 lvl 1 monsters or have bricked. Puppets cause GY setup into Kaiza and Kaiza cause more GY setup either through Super Soldier Soul or Kaiki for Gilti-Gearfried. Why am I using Vanilla BLS? Because Super Soldier ritual Sucks (in this deck at least).  And also because on the off chance that you want to Ritual summon twice.  Why no Pre-Prep? You got 5 cards to get BLS and a Ritual Spell into your hands AND Pre-Prep only gets the vanilla Spell, not Synthesis (which btw lets u summon from the hand and GY, which is why Trade-in is there).

deck_excerpt: Activate Mine, summon the same Kaiju 20 times and dab on your opponent
deck_description:
The end goal of Weather Painters is putting Rainbow Painter on the field and having a bunch of painters on the field ready to be used as ammo for her. This gameplan has 2 big, overlapping issues:
  1. It's impossible to achieve turn 1.
  2. The painters don't offer any meaningful interaction during your opponent's turn in order to survive the turn.
In an attempt to last for long enough to actually get Rainbow out, I'm playing the mother of all floodgates, Mystic Mine. Through Cloudy and Snowy Canvas, you can always keep the number of monsters on your field between 1 and 0 to keep Mine live while you accumulate Painters into rotation, and kill it when you want to push for game. The deck goes second to make Mine live and to take advantage of one of the Painters' strongest interactions, bouncing Kaijus to hand with Thundery Canvas. The Kaijus serve as recurring removal and they help you actually resolve Mine by taking out any spell negates or quick removal your opponent may have without letting your opponent respond.   The ED practically doesn't matter, so I'm just playing a bunch of Maximus targets, a chonky Zeus package and an Accesscode suite, but you can pretty much just play whatever you want. You can probably even add a DPE package in there, but I'm already running a Mine deck and I don't want to overdose on cringe.   The side has barely been tested so it might be a bit janky, but you have a bunch of cards for going first and some backrow hate because the deck kinda struggles against trap decks.

deck_excerpt: Probably most basic six sam deck that ever touched this cursed land.
deck_description: Welcome to my Dojo In this description I will show you how to play six samurais (or at least how i do it, i can bet my strategies aren't consistent) The most important part of this deck is just using gateway of the six to non-stop use Kizan to your advantage and bringing a shit-ton of link monsters and sometimes even synchros and having lots of fun doing it. Perfect hand is Kageki + kizan/grandmaster + any other six sam + shien + gateway Of course this isn't anime, so god hands appear only one in 10 games but thanks to perfect spells that sams posses and also that you rarely brick means that you can make at least one borrelsword. Main gameplan (that I use at least) is: -if you have, place every counter based six sam spell you have (most important of them six gateway and shien's dojo) -normal summon kageki and use his effect to special summon mizuho/shinai -special summon kizan/grandmaster from hand -use kizan and kageki/grandmaster to bring the  great general (make sure that he points to remaining six sams) and use his effect to search gateway (and if you have gateway already just search other spells or use him as additional counter generator) -place gateway on the field (this is where the fun begins, if you have at least 2 counters on dojo i advice to use its effect to bring fumo) -by that point if you had at the start of the game placed gateway, other necessities and summoned general you should have at least 4 counters on the field NOW WE DO A LITTLE BIT OF TROLLING -use effect of gateway to search kizan/granfmaste to add them to hand and special summon them which will fuel the mighty fire which is sim sams counter generating powers -USE GATEWAYS EFFECT AS MUCH AS YOU CAN -if you were lucky to draw shien now is your moment to bring him -use fumo to go into funny synchros like shi en, herald of arc light or draco berserk -use remaining monsters to go into links, like apollousa or borrelsword (tbh rest of the synchro and link cards are here for different situation like beating over stuff or extra firepower. Isolde is here if you don't need great general and lack some samurais, and linkuriboh if your fumo is alone on the field.)

deck_excerpt: Predaplant Albaz deck December 2021 (With new support from Dimension Force)
deck_description: Finally, at long lost, Predaplants can stand on their own two feet as a competitive deck! Kind of! I decided to name it "Yuri the Ravenous Dragon" after Yuri, the power-hungry user of this archetype in Yu-Gi-Oh! ARC-V.  So here is a Predaplant deck profile featuring the new support from Dimension Force and an Albaz engine! Thanks to two of the Pendulum Monsters that Predaplants got, the deck can Fusion Summon and use Predator Counters much more easily! Branded Fusion can be used to send Predaplant Byblisp to the Graveyard, and then search a different Predaplant for further plays.     Ideally, this deck can do good going first or second--having both hand trap negation in the Main Deck and backrow removal in the Side Deck--but for me personally, I tend to do better going first.

deck_excerpt: Oh man this is doing numbers
deck_description: An Onomat deck. It's mostly all just level 4 extenders that aim to get you an endboard of Leo Utopia Ray with Pegasus equipped for 2 monster negates, Zombiestein for an omninegate and a Dragonar with 2 materials leftover that you can use on your opponent's turn to get either a Hope Harbinger, Kragen, or even Bagooska in some really desperate situations, depending on what your opponent does. Going second, you either do like every other deck that plays 2 monsters with the same level and go straight into Zeus (through either Utopia into Prime for a 4-mat Zeus or an attack position Bagooska to ensure you get to summon the Zeus in the first place) or you punch something really hard with Utopia Double.     Before I get shit for running 46 cards, the deck has 3 different engine requirements you really don't want to draw (Double or Nothing, Pegasus and the Rank-Up) and since pretty much every card is just an extender, it doesn't cause consistency issues. If you're completely set on making every one of your decks exactly 40 cards because you have yugituber brain-rot, I'd cut Astral Kuriboh, 1 each of Zubababancho and Onomatopoeia, an Xyz Change Tactics, Shade Brigandine and Armed Sage.  The deck is also not playing F0 because you usually have to do some pretty suboptimal stuff (or draw an absolute god hand) to make it turn 1 and it takes up a lot of Extra Deck space, but feel free to run it if you want to.  Another option to consider is Traptrix Rafflesia with Gravedigger's Trap Hole to avoid dying to Nibiru, but personally I think the deck is running enough bricks already and you need a pretty good hand to summon Rafflesia before you go into Nibiru range and keep going afterwards.

deck_excerpt: Dark Magician with Dogmatika, Invoked, and Sky Striker.
deck_description: You only need 2 Dark Magician, if you want to build a house... play 3. Play 3 Red-Eyes Fusion, those 3 are not bricks! You can use 1 copy to summon Dragoon and the other 2 as discard fodder for Dragoon negate or Magicians' Souls. Some players only play 1 copy, and if their 1 and only copy got negated... then what?   1 card leads to Dragoon: If you meet the condition, you can activate Sky Striker Mobilize - Engage! then search for Sky Striker Mecha - Hornet Drones, activate it to summon 1 Sky Striker Ace Token, tribute that token for Sky Striker Ace - Kagari, using her effect, target Sky Striker Mecha - Hornet Drones from your GY and add it back to your hand. Now use Sky Striker Ace - Kagari as a material to summon Sky Striker Ace - Kaina (you need her link marker), again activate Hornet Drones to summon 1 Sky Striker Ace Token (you will gain 100LP). Use the token as a material to summon Link Spider. At this point, your opponent still thinks you're using a Sky Striker Deck. Now surprise your opponent by sacrificing Kaina and Link Spider to summon the Predaplant Verte Anaconda then summon Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon. (You can also start by just Sky Striker Mecha - Hornet Drones) You can chain link Sky Striker Mecha - Eagle Booster to protect your Anaconda from Effect Veiler or Infinite Impermanence. You can also use it as a Discard Fodder for Dragoon or Magicians' Souls.

deck_excerpt: Symphonic Warriors Deck with small Arrive in Light/Majestic Star Dragon Engine
deck_description:
The Deck is pretty versatile and can get out Synchros of many different Levels. The ones i used are pretty much just examples and you can switch them out with anything (same with the Side). Though i would definitely recommend using Halqifibrax, since Synthess can copy the effect of the Tuner you summon with it and Rocks, since getting back a Symphonic Warrior from the Extra can help alot with extending your combos and it can profit off the Level increase Effect of Basses. In addition to that Stardust Warrior can also be helpful, since it can summon a (face-down) Warrior Rocks, when it leaves the Field (main reason i used 2 copies of Rocks here). You can summon Stardust Warrior relatively easy with any level 7 Synchro plus Halqifibrax tagging into Shooting Riser and sending a Level 4 to the Grave (mainly Synthess to have another free Summon on your next turn). Hi-Speedroid Clear Wing Rider can also be Summoned pretty easily, because most Synchros i used and all the Symphonic Warriors are Wind (Speedroids in general work well with Symphonic Warriors. So do Windwitches and Dragunity.). Virtual World Kyubi can also reset Synthess to use it again (only the Pendulum Symphonic Warriors have hard once per turn Effects). Now to the combos. They can be both very linear and also not. With Deejays/Guitaar to Summon Deejays and Stardust Synchron/Stardust Illumination to mill Synchron in Hand you can directly Summon Majestic Star Dragon or Shooting Majestic Star Dragon (you need Illumination in your Grave to Summon Shooting Majestic Star).
Summon Deejays and Summon another Monster with it's Effect Tribute the seccond Monster with Synchron's Effect search Arrive in Light, activate it and place Converging Wills Dragon on your Deck Tune Deejays with Synchron for Stardust Dragon, Draw the Dragon and Summon it and Brotaur from your Deck with it's Effect (optional) Discard 1 for Brotaur's Effect and Target Stardust to search Arma Gram for another Beater and a Negate on your Turn (you could also search Dragonruler Tempest or Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon, if you are playing around with Dragons more) now you could use the Effect of Illumination to Summon Shooting Majestic Star or just go into the normal Majestic Star
  As for the Symphonic Warriors themselves, they can have some interesting plays depending on what cards you draw (mainly if you have Dress Rehearsal or Symph Amplifire or not). They do however have one 2 Card combo that could be considered as their main starting play.
Summon Deejays and Summon Synthess (face-down) with it's Effect activate Guitaris' Pendulum Effect to bounce itself and Deejays activate Deejays' Pendulum Effect to Flip Synthess face-up Synthess Flip Effect activates to let you Search a Symphonic Warrior-Monster (Miccs and Guitaris can Special themselves, when you have the Spells on the Field and when you have Summoned Deejays via Guitaar and still have your Normal, you can use that Search for another copy of Guitaar for it's Revive on Normal Effect instead. Alternatively you can use Guitaris' on Summon Effect to bounce the Guitaar from your Pendelum Zone to then Summon it) Deejays' Effect activates after Synthess' Effect resolves to Summon itself back to the Field
  This is my first time submitting a Deck, so don't expect it to be the best, but i am having fun with it haha Personally i'm not the biggest fan of Handtraps, so you could probably enhance it yourself by putting in some copies of Ash Blossom and similar. The Deck itself is very fragile, when it has to go against Ash or Nibiru, but when you Draw the Cards you need and don't get disrupted, you can make some impressive Boards. Also before i started with this Deck i haven't played much with Pendulums. I didn't even know that they had to be Summoned from the Extra to Linked Zones haha There might be some generic Pendulum Support that could have helped the Deck lots. Well anyways thanks for taking the time to look at this and if you have a Deck that could profit from another Normal Summon, 3 Guitaar with 1 Miccs might help lol

deck_excerpt: Train OTK (feat. Battle Royal Mode - Joining)
deck_description: I'm not gonna lie, when the Spell "Battle Royal Mode - Joining" was revealed, I was genuinely at a loss on how to use it. The card is casual trash, but I still wanted to think of SOME way to play it well! So after a morning energy drink and some sunny-side up eggs, I had my light bulb moment: I was gonna use it in Trains! I named this particular deck "PAIN TRAIN" after the song "Here Comes The Pain Train" by Jay Harper.     See, Juggernaut Liebe can attack monsters 1 more time for each Xyz Material it has, which means you can target your opponent's Effect Monster with Battle Royal Mode - Joining, so that it has to battle 3 times before it can be destroyed. Liebe can then attack it at least twice (and even use its other effect to increase its ATK to 6000 beforehand) to OTK the opponent!     Because Trains is an unga bunga Deck, you want to go second 110% of the time. I also put a bunch of hand traps, 3 Dark Ruler, and Lightning Storm in the Side Deck in case you are facing a stronger, more competitive Deck.

deck_excerpt: Witchcrafters featuring the new support, designed to be as functional as possible.
deck_description: The goal of the deck is to out-resource your opponent while playing around interactions with the numerous quick-effects of your Monsters. This deck has a nice toolbox of Monsters and Spells, all easily accessible and recyclable, allowing you to outplay and outpace countless other strategies with proper play and a bit of luck. Thanks to the release of the new Fusion Monster Witchcrafter Vice-Master the deck has gotten a much stronger end-boss and a much higher ceiling. As such, it only makes sense to aim to put her onto the field ASAP, and this build tries to do just that. Cards like Magicians' Souls and Magician's Restage, which were previously clunky and unnecessary, are now powerful extenders for producing Predaplant Verte Anaconda. Combined with Magicalized Fusion, this makes it extremely easy to get out Vice-Master turn 1 and get the ball rolling. Generic spellcaster Link-1s make link-climbing even easier, and the nearly entirely spellcaster Extra Deck synergizes extremely well with Vice-Master to allow for some disgusting turn 3+ plays, especially as the typing in this deck allows you to make every Charmer link, as well as Selene , Queen of the Master Magicians (who can also be used to reborn/trigger Vice-Master as a quick-effect). Furthermore, nearly every extra deck monster can be recycled with Patronus, allowing you to easily manipulate the board state turn after turn. My ratios and reasoning are as follows: 3x Witchcrafter Schmietta: Hands-down the best of the starters both in statline and effect. Vice-Master allows you to get creative with your plays involving Schmietta, as you can often mill a card and then quickly add it to your hand to be used (such as Patronus) 3x Witchcrafter Genni: Not quite as good as Schmietta, but she has enough utility that I run her at 3. She's the best way of accessing Golem Aruru early on, and can allow you to play through interruptions depending on your hand, but she can occasionally be dead with nothing to copy. You could easily cut her to 2 or even 1, but I've so far liked having a decent number of starters to work with. 2x Witchcrafter Pittore: She can help cycle dead cards out of your hand, but generally she's just worse than the previous two. I run 2 just to keep up the number of names in the deck, but you could easily play 1-0. 1x Witchcrafter Potterie: Deceptively powerful in the right situations, Potterie helps keep cards in your hand and enables comeback plays if you ever end up in a situation where you're stuck topdecking. That being said, I would probably never play more than 1 as she's typically only good past turn 1. 1x each of Witchcrafter Golem Aruru, Madame Verre, Haine and Edel: The big bosses are all huge bricks and as such should never be ran at anything higher than 1. You can access them all extremely easily, recycle them from nearly anywhere, and Vice-Master gives you an Extra Deck boss in case you somehow lose them all. Of these, Edel is the worst and is usually only good in corner cases where you draw into the other bosses, but her being summonable off of Vice-Master does allow for some interesting plays. 3x Magicians' Souls: While Souls used to be mostly pointless to run, it now serves as an extremely efficient card for setting up a fusion of Vice-Master off of Magicalized Fusion and can be used as an extender to make Verte. Furthermore, Souls cycles spells out of your hand to dig deeper into your deck, and in combination with Magician's Restage allows you to generate a ton of resources early on (as you can summon Souls, link it off, activate Restage, revive Souls, then use Souls to send Restage and draw + get the search off of Restage and make Verte for Vice-Master). I would certainly not drop this anymore, and have even considered playing the new Dark Magician Ritual Monster (Illusion of Chaos) to search it. 3x Witchcrafter Creation, Holiday and Unveiling: Creation gets you your monsters, Holiday is your best extender through disruptions, and Unveiling makes your cards unrespondable for a turn. Ratios of the spells are somewhat flexible but I wouldn't cut more than 1-2 between Holiday and Unveiling. 1x Witchcrafter Draping, Collaboration, Bystreet, Scroll and Confusion: The "bad" spells, all ran at 1. Each one has its use and serves as another name in the deck, but you can afford to cut these down if you want more room. Scroll and Collaboration are especially niche and tend to be winmore when actually using them beyond discard fodder, but Draping, Bystreet and Confusion are all solid enough to warrant running them at 1. 3x Magicalized Fusion: In combination with any starter, Magicalized Fusion cheats out Vice-Master and gets your gameplan moving. All of the level 4 or lower Witchcrafters can be linked off for Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden, giving you the required materials for Vice-Master instantly. Furthermore, it can easily be sent off of Verte Anaconda at basically any point to give you a secondary way of accessing Vice-Master if your plays get interrupted. I would run at least the 1, but since opening it is ideal, I personally play 3. 3x Magician's Restage + 1 each of Magician's Left/Right Hand: Restage is just another extender/recovery option, much like Holiday, but can also be traded out for a decent floodgate in the form of the Left/Right Hands. If nothing else, Restage is the best discard fodder in the deck, and enables some nice plays with Magicians' Souls. To make things even better, neither effect is a HOPT, so opening multiple is rarely an issue. I play 3/1/1, but you could play around with the ratios if you so choose. 2x Witchcrafter Patronus: The only Trap in the deck, Patronus allows you to cycle resources and keep spells in your hand in the grind game. As Vice-Master can recover it from the GY, it is now "searchable" off of Schmietta/Vice-Master and as such I only play the 2 copies (1 to use and 1 as a backup/for the banish effect), but you could easily play 3 or 1 depending on your preference. 2x Witchcrafter Vice-Master: The boss monster of the deck, Vice-Master is everything you could ever want and more. She raises the ceiling of your end board, gives you more disruption, keeps monsters on your field and cards in your hand. All 3 of her effects are good, she's easy to make and can be revived/recycled as required. I play 2 as sometimes it's easier to summon a new one than to recycle an old one, but you could get away with 1 copy if you desired. 1x Relinquished Anima and Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden: Both link 1s serve as a way of getting Witchcrafters/Magicians' Souls into the GY for their effects, to be revived to extend into Verte, or to be used with Magicalized Fusion. Furthermore, these allow you to easily go into Lyna/Dharc using the small Witchcrafters on turn 3+ to push for lethal with Selene + Accesscode Talker. 1x Verte Anaconda: The easiest way to make Vice-Master, and a nice backup option after your plays get interrupted. Easy to make and typically only needed once, so I play just the 1 copy. 1x of Hiita, Wynn, Eria, Aussa, Lyna and Dharc (the Charmer Links): As this deck has a member of each attribute, you can make any of these depending on what you need at any given moment. Their spellcaster typing also means that they trigger Vice-Master and can be recycled with Patronus, not to mention that they all ladder into Selene using the stolen monster they summon. I like having one of each of them, but feel free to cut the ones you need less if you find yourself wanting more room. 1x Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians: Selene is an absolutely insane card in this deck, allowing for all sorts of weird plays once your engine has been established. She triggers Vice-Master as a quick-effect, can summon any Witchcrafter from hand/GY, and can be recycled with Patronus. The high Spell count of the deck means she'll almost always have a good number of Spell Counters on summon. Selene also enables an exact lethal OTK by making a 5300 ATK Accesscode Talker + the 2700 ATK Vice-Master, and this can be done extremely easily using the Charmer links. 1x Knightmare Unicorn, Accesscode Talker and Underworld Goddess of the Closed World: The utility links. Knightmare Unicorn is for niche cases where you need a non-destructive removal option quickly, Accesscode is for breaking boards and pushing for game, and Underworld Goddess is for outing problematic monsters (Dragoon, The Arrival Cyberse, an I:P-boosted Avramax, etc.). All 3 of these are easily accessed thanks to the Charmer links and Vice-Master, which allow you to amass a surprisingly high number of bodies (hence the inclusion of Underworld Goddess). (The side deck is fairly experimental. I've found that removal like Evenly and Kaijus tends to be better than other board breakers, but I'm on the fence about cards like Secret Village of the Spellcasters and Lava Golem as they can occasionally be useless/harmful)

deck_excerpt: Most optimized pure version I'm playing in this format and discussion about deckbuild choices and also talking about DPE version.
deck_description: First let's talk about the main deck structure: as shown in the decklist the deck uses 8 extenders in the form of low level insects and has 9 main Normal Summons which are Scout Buggy, Sting the Poison and Resonance Insect and 3 Pseudo Starters which are 2 Gokipole and 1 Retaliating "C". From the high level insects we have 4 options and the Gadarla is not necessarily part of the priority targets of the Resonance Insect as it does not generate any type of combo but an interruption to be accessed when necessary. The number of Normal Summons and Extender should be high because you need to have a two-card combination to make any combo as you need to access the extra deck's Links for your engine to spin out of inertia and how costly this task is once you is Link-2 or higher you need that amount of cards for the deck to work. As these Link-2 Picofalena and Armor Horn are very sensitive to interactions, you often depend on your Starters to be able to bypass any hand traps or other interactions on these cards and that's why Sting the Poison, Resonance Insect and Gokipole are key pieces in the deck's operation as they are very versatile and can be a interrupt against annoying monsters like Winda in the case of Sting the Poison or adding Sting Lancer and Gadarla in the case of Resonance Insect or Vanilla for the hand with Gokipole and that way you build your field while handles opponent's interactions. Because of that we have to use Gold Sarcophagus and Foolish Burial in the deck to have access to these cards as soon as possible mostly sending Gokipole to the GY which becomes a Resonance Insect search for the hand or a Vanilla interrupt, but it also happens that sometimes you don't have extenders on hand to access the extra deck's Links and that way you add Arbalest the Rapidfire for the hand that becomes two bodies on the field. Well, why did I just talk about Starters and mention Gokipole a lot (which isn't even a Normal Summon right and yes you want to send it to the gy somehow) but not Scout Buggy? Because the Scout Buggy by itself doesn't help you deal with interactions because it's just a "Tour Guide" for itself but in the pure version of the deck it's a good starter and also the only efficient way to make Cicada King besides mainly being an excellent follow up for the existence of Field Spell Beetrooper Formation having a lot of use every turn in GY which improves the grind game that is the objective of this deck: take the opponent to the grind game and have a more advantageous exchange of resources. Other reasons why it is excellent in the pure version is because it is the second best option for a deck special with Invincible Atlas and that happens a lot. About Sting Lancer, Scale Bomber and Beetrooper Spells/Traps used in the main deck: There was a time when I really liked using 3 Sting Lancer (because it's the best Beetrooper card in the game so far) but first I noticed that you never want to draw 2 copies in the starting hand becoming a brick, second in this format the number of hand traps that activate being discarded to gy decreased so it's very difficult for his effect to stay alive on turn 1, third that even with the high amount of cards good to return to the deck in this format thanks to Verte Anaconda and his friend Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer the Sting Lancer is so easily accessible and recyclable that really 2 copies is the ideal number. About Scale Bomber I rarely take advantage of his interaction effect on the field but I keep maximizing it to 3 as he can chain block his Normal Summon but it sure is a card that can be reduced to 2 copies post side just like I do with Battlewasp's special summon extenders. About me not using Assault Roller I say that I never found the card good compared to Vanilla, although it can be an extender even if you have it in your hand the fact is that this deck has few ways to interact with the established field of opponent and Vanilla is one of the few options that the deck has access to destroy the opponent's cards and that's why I consider it a card 10 times better than the Assault Roller besides not needing to ban gy resources to enter the field. In short it is an extender and brick in the same way as Assault Roller but its cost-effectiveness is much better and rewarding, it is so necessary that whenever it is possible to return it to the deck you return it to make Gokipole an interaction/extender. Why not use the Heavy Beetrooper Mighty Neptune? When the Spoiler from Beetrooper's supports were all known I saw him as the best among them all because he fixes the problem of banishing several Insects and not having to recycle them back to the deck but in practice it turned out to be a very bad card that brick every starting hand you see her and even in long grind game matches where you get 10 Banned Bugs I didn't miss him in the deck at all. So I currently consider it an unnecessary brick. In the future if the deck gets new support it may improve. The spell Beetrooper Descent has many advantages to be used but at the same time many disadvantages: The first advantage is that it is very beneficial to have 3 targets for the Sting Lancer to add to the hand throughout the game and this is very relevant. Second it makes the Sting Lancer two bodies on the field which is important when you are playing after suffering interruptions from the opponent. Third it is a spell/trap out when you have the Invincible Atlas on the field. But it brings many disadvantages that make the difference that is the case to create a token which does not become an Insect in GY to banish with Armor Horn and Doom Dozer and this lack of resources makes you not able to continue playing or need to do so unoptimized plays and banish Bugs that shouldn't be banned, second that the destroy spell/trap effect doesn't prove as excellent against trap decks as it seems: often your opponent knows you added it with the Sting Lancer and throws around it activate Ice Dragon's Prison in Standby Phase to banish the Invincible Atlas and that way you can no longer destroy backrow and the worst thing is that it needs to first create the token and then destroy cards so it simply won't work on the There Can Be Only One effect which is the worst Floodgate against the deck being a card that leaves a lot to be desired against trap match. To be honest cards like Resonance Insect, Gokipole and Arbalest the Rapidfire are much more important to win matches against Anti-meta and backrow decks because they have excellent floating effects if they let the field and trap deck destroy the opponent's monsters at all times to control the field. About Extra Deck I have to comment that the existence of Almiraj is one of the reasons why I don't maximize Retaliating "C" because it simply cannot become an Almiraj and also because the search targets are the worst compared to the versatility of the Gokipole and the Resonance Insect. Almiraj is also very important to play around cards like Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer and Dogmatika Punishment besides being the way the deck can access Knightmare Phoenix under the There Can Be Only One effect since it is Cyberse and you can then summon from an Insect and make phoenix to pop the TCBO and keep playing after that so it's an essential card in this deck and its gy effect isn't hard to use either because like your Normal Summon bugs most trigger effects when destroyed by battle too so it's not It's unusual for you to go into the battle phase and destroy your own monsters like the Resonance Insect, Gokipole and Arbalest the Rapidfire that activate excellent floating effects. Shinobi Insect is a card that should only be used because it is relevant that it is a Link-2 Insect made using two monsters with different names and also it is a free insect to be banned in the GY in place of other important insects, besides being a of the cards that help you play about the effect of Gozen Match until you manage to destroy it. Wind Pegasus is the extra deck flexible spot and I've already tested using the second Seraphim Papillion, Topologic Trisbaena and Battlewasp - Halberd the Charge but in this format I've been facing a lot of decks that use Dogmatika Maximus and I see Wind Pegasus as an excellent card to use against these strategies to make Winda with Schism. It's also not hard to make because of Primitive Butterfly + Sting the Poison becoming an out for Gozen Match so it has its uses in the deck. As I don't particularly do an aggressive endboard playing with this deck as most players go through with Counter Trap and Seraphim Papillion to reborn Sting the Poison on the opponent's turn I don't miss the second Seraphim Papillion but I confess it is very annoying having to shuffle him back to the extra deck every turn and the fear of seeing him banned from the gy by the opponent and not having access to him for the rest of the game but this risk I've been punished practically never until now and that's why I decide to keep keeping a versatility card like Wind Pegasus. About the Side deck I usually don't make big changes from the main deck to the side deck because it's no use filling the deck with tech cards and not having plays after stopping the opponent so I think the side deck is balanced for the problems that the deck faces. Solemn Judgment is essential when you go first with this deck because postside the opponent will have a lot of hate backrow like Lightning Storm and Evenly Matched because you know you don't go through with monster interactions on the field, your interactions are all spell/trap zone and in your hand you will then receive a lot of side cards that Solemn Judgment denies. On the DPE version that ranked second on the Remote Duel YCS Europe: This version of the deck focused on DPE Turbo makes sense because you trade the bad stuff in the deck, which is the scarcity of extra-deck monsters, to the Insect type. it makes it torture to play with the deck lock on Insects because you have nowhere to go and the win condition is very weak. So instead of lock-in on Insects why not choose to end up with a real win condition called Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer? That's the result. Not to mention that in this version you remove all the engine cards that don't help your deck play because one of the worst things about Beetrooper is the fact that you use a lot of one-offs that you never want to see in your hand because they are searchable and they are just part of your end board, they don't help the deck's resilience and that makes a difference in the deck's performance throughout a tournament. This deck's Bricks are very painful to buy but necessary to have a respectable grind game but the win condition is so weak that you don't even make the grind game most of the time, so this approach of focusing on passing with Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer and cutting out all the bad vibes the deck uses makes perfect sense. The deck has Link Climb power, the engine is good but it is the DPE together with Verte Anaconda that makes the deck viable and for sure this is a deck that has its days numbered because it is impossible to imagine that in the next banlist Verte Anaconda will continue in the game because it is the biggest problem of this format, the number of games I forgive is countless because of the existence of Verte Anaconda in the game. I don't think it's wrong that there are power spells that fuse the deck, I'm not mad at the guy activating Fusion Destiny but for sure he has the option to use Anaconda for that is unjustifiable. You have to choose to hold the best interaction of your deck like Counter Trap Beetrooper Fly&Sting for Anaconda instead of the opponent's engine cards and this creates something very toxic in the game where the opponent is forcing your interactions just to be guaranteed be able to solve Verte Anaconda because it wins games for you and that has to end. That's why I think the pure version of Beetrooper will improve a lot with the banning of Verte Anaconda because the game is fairer where you can give interactions in the opponent's deck engine and not have to play around Verte Anaconda. The DPE version only exists because of this broken Link-2 that should have been banned a long time ago. Combos about the deck I made available in this article and they are still valid because BODE supports haven't changed the way the deck plays: https://ygoprodeck.com/Forum/ and in the Article Discussion look for the topic: "INTRODUCING THE BEETROOPER ARCHETYPE"

deck_excerpt: Predaplant being a combo fusion deck. Heroes aren't the poster boys of fusion no more.
deck_description: Predaplants is a very hardcore fusion deck. They fuse as extenders and fuse as final board presence. You can go all fusion only and have the albaz fusion on but you can also do a mix of links, synchro and fusions. There are even options to side in more cards if you want.  When searching predaplant cards, search predapruning if you can first, then some of the effect monsters, and use the pendulum link to search the scale you are missing. I tend to have 5 searches each time.  Not fusion locked tips: Odd-eyes synchron is easy enough to use to make baronne after you fuse the scales to make a random fusion and get the scale 8 back in hand. I also like to have a preda counter on the link monster since it alters levels unless you want that and that way you can summon back the level one from grave.  Fusion locked tips: Cards that locks you under fusion; branded fusion and predapractice. Always send the level one predaplant with the branded fusion. Then of course there is the preda counter strategy that is pure fusion strategy really. There are 5 fusion cards and lots of ways to get materials.  My favorite searchable way to place counters is the trap predaplanning that can foolish the level one on your opponents turn for a search. I want to use necro fusion more but I do tend to have all my cards on board before needing it.

Using the Anaconda strat kinda works in the deck, but I have never really used it when I did use the deck. I added deployment just in case, but you can replace it with some handtraps, the same with lightning storm as that card is really expensive. The main weakness is negates and background removal, which is why I added Twin Twisters and Lightning Storm. But overall I've seen success with this deck.

deck_excerpt: This deck focused on using the banish-recycle of the Metaphys Archetype with Necroface and looping it until you can create an extra link out of the Ex
deck_description: This deck focused on using the banishment characteristic of the Metaphys Archetype and recycling it with Necroface and looping it until you can create an extra link out of the Extra Deck. This deck is most successful when you start as the second-turn player. You need to analyst the opponent's move at the first turn to make your strategy work on them. Make sure you get Macro Cosmos / Dimensional Fissure either with Left Arm Offering or by drawing them. You can also use Left Arm Offering to banish Necroface in your hand, or when there's none of them in your hand try to get Gold Sarcophagus and then start banishing your opponent monsters by selecting Necroface and then activating the banished Metaphys card. Protect your fragile monster with getting Metaphys Decoy Dragon that will banish itself to summon disruptive monster such as Metaphys Daedalus (can banishing all special summoned monster) or Metaphys Nephthys (can banishing all set spell/trap card) or you can summon Metaphys Ragnarok to enhance your chance of banishing Necroface. Protect yourself from getting decked out by special summoning Nemeses Keystone from your hand by recovering Necroface in your Banish Zone. Getting your flow stuck because of your key card in the Graveyard? Banish them face-down by using Five-Headed Link Dragon and then recycle them using Necroface. Five-Headed Link Dragon can also become your immune beatstick to pulverize your opponent LP. Another option for your immune beatstick by summoning Link-6 @Ignister to your field. When they summoned immune boss monsters such as Dark Dragoon, Phoenix Enforcer, etc; use Sphere Mode or Kaiju to shut them down.

deck_excerpt: A "Cyberdark" Deck is a varied Deck primarily focusing on Beatdown and Control. The Deck uses Machine monsters primarily and Dragon monsters secondari
deck_description: A Cyberdark Deck focuses on the use of machine cards, with dragon cards supporting. Making a proper build of this deck type requires good spell and trap cards that help fill up the graveyard quickly, so you can take advantage of discard cards like Tribute to the Doomed and Monster Reincarnation. Future Fusion and Foolish Burial are also effective for getting level 3 or lower dragons in the graveyard. Fusion monsters are used as auxiliary backup, being formed from, Cyberdark Impact!, Overload Fusion, and Dragon's Mirror they require that there be proper material monsters in the grave, making the use of them late game only, unless used in conjunction with Future Fusion. Virus cards can be used for addition advantage because Cyberdark monsters span the spectrum of their requirements. Synchro support comes in the form of level 7 and 6 monsters specifically Goyo Guardian, Dark Strike Fighter and Black Rose Dragon Cyberdark Horn, Cyberdark Edge, and Cyberdark Keel in addition to having equipping effects each have a unique addition damage ability that punishes defensive play by an opponent. Cyberdark Horn, Cyberdark Edge, and Cyberdark Keel deliver piercing, direct, and burn damage respectively. Cyberdarks are by themselves very weak monsters, with only 800 attack points, even a skilled duelist will get nervous using a deck like this, it has a lot of weaknesses, being near completely aggressive, relying on the grave to gain momentum, and weak against anti-monster spell/trap cards. Another looming threat is that the opponent turn this deck's graveyard against the duelist, like by using Monster Reborn on a Blue-Eyes White Dragon. A threat like this can be remedied by using dragons that are difficult to special summon like Yamata Dragon and Tyrant Dragon, or even dragons that cannot be special summoned from the graveyard like Diabolos, King of the Abyss, Light and Darkness Dragon, Armed Dragon LV10, Armed Dragon LV7, Dark Armed Dragon, Rainbow Dragon, or Rainbow Dark Dragon. Ultimately, the high level dragon monsters used for Cyberdark Dragon in this deck comes down to the duelist's taste. If he or she wants to play it safe, then the aforementioned dragons can be used. If the duelist enjoys the Red-Eyes Black Dragon or Blue-Eyes White Dragon cards, they splash in very well. If the duelist wants to use a lot of Synchro Monster, then this deck can be easily geared towards powerful Synchro Dragons as well. Factors in deciding this depend on whether the deck is Dragon or Machine focused, and Fusion or Synchro focused. The effects of the Cyberdarks only activate when they are Normal Summoned and cards such as Compulsory Evacuation Device, Pulling the Rug and Solemn Judgment will negate them. If a Cyberdark is in the graveyard, use Monster Reincarnation to discard a low level dragon and get the Cyberdark back in your hand and then re-summon it again and equip it with the dragon that was just discarded. Dark Eruption is a very good card for this deck too. A nice little trick is to use Dark Armed Dragon or Light and Darkness Dragon to be equiped to Cyberdark Dragon. Both have 2800 attack which brings Cyberdark Dragon to 3800 not including the monsters in the grave. With Light and Darkness Dragon, when he's destroyed while being treated as an equip card, his second effect will still activate, wiping your field and summoning any monster from your grave. This can be useful if you just tributed your dragon for a virus, or if it was killed by a spell or trap such as Mirror Force.
