deck_excerpt: Break boards, bones, and faces, to run your opponent over with TRAINS OTK!!!
deck_description:
Trains has always been my favorite deck and I will always try my hardest to make them compete with the current meta. Trains ALWAYS want to go second if you have the choice. If you have to go first, Dragoon is your best option. It's pretty easy to get two monsters on board to make Verte with how trains work. Dora is your second best option if you have to go first (if you know they can out Dragoon easily). In some special cases you can even make both going first!!! In a recent regional tournament I had a judge rule that Interrupted Kaiju Slumber WILL WORK under Barrier Statue of the Stormwinds' lock as long as one of the targets is a wind monster. So take that ruling with a grain of salt because that's not how it actually works. That makes Gadarla, the Mystery Dust Kaiju your best out to Floowandereeze at the moment.
  • The Kaiju engine is to help break your opponents board by removing problem monsters and possibly getting you even more level 10 monsters. Three Jizukiru and Gadarla to help the chances of opening one of them, and only 2 Slumbers because if you draw one Kaiju you would make the third Slumber a dead card in the deck. One Kaiju card + Night Express Knight + Derricrane is usually enough for an OTK in most cases. Kaiju the problem, summon Express, Special Derricrane, XYZ into Gustav and burn for 2000. Then use Derricrane's effect to destroy the Kaiju. Overlay into Liebe, activate effect to make ATK 6000 and punch for game.
  • Switchyard is your bread and butter. Don't have the level 10 you need? Just pitch what you don't want and add what you do. Switchyard gets shut down hard by Ash Blossom unfortunately; so you need to try to bait the Ash first if you really need that search.
  • Switchyard + Pegasus +Bullet Train = 3 level 10s. Switchyard to pitch Bullet adding Derricrane. Summon Pegasus, activate effect to special Bullet from grave chaining Derricrane. If you already have those three monsters in hand, pitch Bullet to add Bullet, then do the combo again. Only this time you activate the second Bullet in hand for 4 level 10s. That's either a Liebe and a Dora, or a Dora and Dragoon, whichever board is stronger against your opponent.
  • Try not to make both Zeus and Dragoon at the same time, they just counter each other and you'll usually end up sending your Dragoon to the grave when you don't want to.
  • Urgent Schedule is one of the best cards in the deck. Depending how good or bad your hand is, you can easily end on a Liebe with Dora protection. Or, it'll save you during the battle phase by summoning two monsters (in defense) to absorb some damage. The two best monsters to summon off this are Ruffian and Bullet Train because of their end phase effects to get the cards you need into your hand.
  • One funny combo happens when you have Switchyard on field, Urgent Schedule set, a level 10 in the grave, and a derricrane in hand. During your opponent's battle or end phase, activate Urgent Schedule to summon two monsters. Then, activate Switchyards effect to summon a level 4 and it becomes a level 10. Summon Pegasus making it a 10, then activate Pegasus' effect to summon the level 10 from grave chaining Derricrane so that Pegasus' effect won't be negated. 5 monsters summoned during your opponent's turn and they can't even Nibiru you (if you did it during their end phase). Make Dora first for protection on your turn, then do whatever combo you want that will hit them the hardest.
  • Bullet Train and Ruffian are two very good cards you always want to send to the grave to get their effects. Ruffian gets you a level 10 Earth Machine from the deck and Bullet gets you ANY MACHINE from you grave. Adding back Pegasus for more combos next turn or Jizukiru to make your opponent worry about losing their boss monster if they can't win that turn. Trains is a mind game that makes your opponent overthink.
  • When your opponent over extends, Nibiru them. A nicely timed Nib can stop a lot of decks. Unfortunately, Nib stops some combos, mainly with Bullet Train, but all you need to do is summon one other monster and you can Verte into Dragoon with ease.
  • Angher Knuckle is there for when you can't XYZ summon to try to stall for a turn. It does have very good synergy with Bullet Train for card recursion though.
  • Pentestag is there to poke through your opponent's defenses if need be.
  • Phoenix and Robot Destroyer are there for backrow removal. Destroyer into Liebe into Zeus gets him 4 to 5 material depending on what effects you use, so that makes a nicely stacked Zeus for your opponent to deal with.
  • Skypalace with a Derricrane attached is two pops and a 1000 burn that you can overlay Liebe onto.
  • BLS is a good option for a lot of decks that do a lot of targeting or destroying like Altergeist. You also make it the correct way with at least one material being a level 7 or higher monster.
  • I know it's weird to not main any hand traps, but with the Kaijus, I haven't really had a problem breaking boards.
With everything said and done, this is my current Trains deck and I usually end up in the top 4 with three other meta decks (we usually always split top 4). Nothing will ever come close to the greatness that is TRAINS OTK!!!!

deck_name: Only Bust 4 Dragon Linx... (ft. Fallen of Albaz)
deck_excerpt: Plainly disgusting Dragon Link build that brings together the Buster Blader lock and 2022's most anticipated Super Poly-with-dragon-wings hero: Fallen
deck_description: Let's get one big thing out of the way right up top: Most of the credit for this remarkable Buster Blader-Dragon Link deck belongs to Tim Rokov and his series of deck profile and combo videos on The Wiseguys TCG YouTube channel. I don't know Tim personally nor do I have any affiliation, formal or otherwise, with The Wiseguys TCG, channel, which is based in Kansas City--far from my hometown. Nevertheless, I would be remiss to not recognize Tim's contribution to deck-building theory around Buster Blader and Dragon Link in general. Tim topped his locals with a version of this deck I'm about to profile, and then proceeded to go on a multi-week (4+ if [Destruction Sword] memory serves me) undefeated tear at locals with his now-infamous Dragon Link-Fallen of Albaz deck. He's obviously not the first to run Buster Blader with Dragon Link, but this particular build is remarkably strong and solves a lot of the contradictions Destruction Sword decks often face, not least among them being how to play through disruptions. If this seems like a shameless plug, check out Tim and The Wiseguys TCG's videos and see for yourself. For my money, he's probably the best and most creative Buster Blader player in the U. today. YGOProDeck won't allow me to directly link to the YouTube video, so those who want to see Tim's deck should search for 'TOP 4 BUSTER BLADER DRAGON LINK DECK PROFILE FT. TIM - GAME CAFE !' on The Wiseguys TCG YouTube channel. Buuuusted Buster Blader Of all the Duel Monsters-era archetypes in YuGiOh, it often surprises newer players to learn that the most competitively viable among them at present is Buster Blader (also called Destruction Sword). This is not my opinion. As recent as summer of this year (2021), Buster Blader decks were taking respectable finishes in remote duel invitationals around the world, fueled in part--though not entirely--by the Dragon Link-dominated format before Guardragon Elpy got whacked. In May 2020,  Nikolas Konikkos took a relatively pure Destruction Sword deck through day-2 of the Niagra YCS tournament, putting the archetype on the map as a potential answer to DLink players everywhere. Other than the small and opportunistic Dragoon package, which requires players to run at least a single copy of Dark Magician to serve as fusion material, none of the other classic YGO icons have seen anything close to Buster's competitive success in recent years. The reasons are pretty obvious to anyone familiar with the deck. Even by comparison with bigger YGO icons like Blue-Eyes White Dragon or Dark Magician, Buster Blader's Destruction Sword archetype has a remarkable amount of support available at this point. Destruction Sword/Buster Blader, technically two different archetypes for gameplay purposes, has its own fusion boss monster, level-8 synchro monster and one of the easiest Link-2s to make of all time. Trap cards like Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman avoid so many of the pitfalls of traps in general, sending the Buster fusion spell to the graveyard for cost and thus making it Ash-proof. Shortly after Union Carrier took its place on the Forbidden list, Buster Blader finally had its most potent control weapon returned to him, namely the Dragon Buster Destruction Sword that can completely lock an opponent out of using their extra deck. Admittedly, Buster Blader decks are always going to have their best times when dragon-heavy decks predominate the format. Dragon Link isn't what it once was, falling precipitously to newer decks like Swordsoul and new blends on old recipes, like Dogmatika-Invoked-Shaddolls. Any given day and all things being equal, a competent Buster deck will wipe the floor with a competent dragon deck, DLink or not, but with fewer DLink decks running around in this format, the natural advantage it enjoyed isn't exactly actionable. That being said, what makes Buster Blader work so well is its devastating, infamous Buster lock. So long as you have a dragon in the graveyard, resolving Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman will special summon Buster Dragon, a level-8 synchro dark dragon, whose effect turns all of the opponent's monsters into dragons. But if the player chooses to send another trap, Destruction Sword Memories, to the graveyard for Prologue's cost, they will also immediately summon out Buster Blader, the Dragon Destroyer Swordsman--a level-8 fusion who (1) turns all dragons on the opponent's field to defense mode; (2) negates the effects of all dragons on the opponent's side of the field; (3) gains 1000 ATK for every dragon the opponent controls or has in-grave; and (4) inflicts piercing damage to monsters in defense position. If that wasn't enough, Buster Dragon also allows a player to equip a Destruction Sword card in the graveyard to any Buster Blader monster--whether the OG Buster Blader, the retrain Buster Blader, the Destruction Swordmaster, or the fusion--on the opponent's turn. There are three Destruction Sword equip monsters with varying effect, but in general, the only one that absolutely must make the main deck is a single copy of Dragon Buster Destruction Sword. Once equipped, the opponent cannot summon from their extra deck. Wizard Buster Destruction Sword, which as far as I'm concerned makes for an excellent side-deck inclusion at x1 in this format, turns off effects from activating in your opponent's graveyard, making it a great antidote to Invoked-Shaddolls decks. Robot Buster Destruction Sword, the third and least useful, restricts your opponent from activating the effects of spells and traps that are already face-up--potentially useful in some circumstances but it doesn't do enough to earn a spot in the deck, main or side. The Buster lock is incredibly strong, effectively turning off many key avenues of play for the opponent with the successful resolution of a single card. Buster Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman, a level-1 light dragon tuner, helps tremendously by searching out any Destruction Sword card and adding it to hand if normal summoned. If you have a way to get Buster Whelp into the graveyard--linking off, perhaps--before activating Prologue, it's a one-stop shop for setting up the basic Buster lock, serving as the generic 1 Dragon-type material requirement for making the Buster Blader fusion off of Destruction Sword Memories. With a murderers row of trap cards at its disposal, running Trap Trick x3 substantially raises the odds of getting Prologue set in your opening hand, one way or another. The deck's reliability, lightweight core engine and oppressive control aspects make it a very solid rogue-tier deck choice. Weapons of Mass Destruction Sword: Buster Blader in Dragon Link Without gilding the lily here, DLink puts some meat on the Buster Blader skeleton. To function optimally, the Buster Blader core requires running just 10-12 cards, meaning that it can fit nicely into a variety of other decks and coexist nicely with other archetypes. DLink, maybe ironically, is one of these synergistic decks that provide alternate win conditions and boost the consistency and reliability of establishing and, crucially, keeping the Buster lock in-place. Capable of putting up formidable boards loaded with disruption on its own, a disciplined DLink/Buster player has alternate routes to make Buster Dragon beyond simply resolving Prologue, which itself has the drawback of destroying your special-summoned Buster Dragon during the end phase of the following turn. After all, it's a level-8 synchro--something DLink can consistently make with ease. Dragon Link decks are known for their powerful starters and seemingly endless extenders, much of which results in a heavy graveyard full of dragons and other useful cards after turn-1. Dragons in-grave helps resolve Destruction Sword Memories, sure, but DLink's extenders give the player ways to follow up if somehow the opponent outs the Buster lock. The temptation, though, is to just plop the 12-card Buster engine on top of a 40+ card Dragon Link deck. Theoretically this isn't a huge problem so long as ratios are kept correct. DLink already has outstanding search capacity and the powerful aforementioned starters/extenders to get things going. The problem is the extra deck. Conservatively, the Buster engine could take up as few as 2 cards in the extra deck, but even with cards like Chaos Space to recycle, this will likely leave the player unable to make followup plays in the event of serious disruption. General wisdom tends to say, 2x Buster Blader, the Dragon Destroyer Swordsman, 2x Buster Dragon, 1x Protector Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman. But while Buster's footprint in the main deck is light, he's taking up solidly a third of the extra deck. There's no way to run a full suite of the usual suspects in DLink, which also means that certain main deck staples are just not as necessary--even if they might be useful. Case in point, I'm not running the Dragonmaid package here. We have plenty of trap-based disruption available as it is, and while this modest three-card package punches far, far above its weight, the deck can't go much higher than 45 cards and maintain its consistency. There's also a growing consensus that in a format marked by liberal use of Droll & Lock Bird, Black Metal Dragon is a safer starter than Starliege Seyfert. I'm not sure if I agree, although I've split the difference here and put both BMD and Starliege at x2. Similarly, the Rokket package here is far more modest and streamlined than a typical Dragon Link deck should run. Rokket Tracer x2 is a recognition of the importance of the synchro summon in this deck--worth more here than Rokket Synchron's extender effect. Absorouter and Noctovision are run at x1 each, though I would consider upping Nocto to x2 because of its little-used tertiary effect in-graveyard to protect cards set in the back-row. At any rate, the deck has plenty of level-1 tuners to make a level-8 synchro play in a pinch. Hell, even Buster Blader and the retrain are level-7 monsters. Busted Branded: Fallen of Albaz as Additional Disruptions in DLink Whether I'm running the Buster stuff at all or just playing a standard Dragon Link deck, Fallen of Albaz will be in the main deck--and at least three potential targets for his Super Poly-like effect will be in the extra deck. Because Albaz is a level-4 dark dragon-type, he's quite at home in DLink and synergizes well with the rest of the deck. Starliege Seyfert and Chaos Space, for instance, can pitch him to search White Dragon Wyverburster. In a pinch, he can even get our link plays started as a normal summon, allowing us to go into Striker Dragon and search the Boot. But Albaz is more than another level-4 body. Ideally he doesn't show up in an opening hand, but I don't want to accidentally mill my only copy off of Chaos Ruler either. Running Albaz at x2 seems to work best since he's not a complete brick-draw either. Any worthwhile DLink deck is making Hieratic Seal of Heavenly Spheres as part of its end-board--preferably sooner rather than later in the event of a Nibiru cataclysm. When tributed, Spheres will special summon out a dragon from the deck or hand at 0 / 0, making the effect of whatever dragon summoned from the deck all the more important. In the past, Omni Dragon Broutar was the go-to pick in order to search out Chaos Dragon Levianeer. More recently, Chamber Dragonmaid became the gold-standard for its ability to search its recyclable bounce-trap, Dragonmaid Tidying, immediately upon hitting the field. Fallen of Albaz offers even greater disruption when summoned off of Spheres' tribute effect. So long as the player has a valid fusion target and a card in-hand to discard--which is easy enough since Spheres can bounce a card from your side of the field as well--Albaz's effect will trigger upon hitting the field, fusing off itself and an opponent's monster as materials for one of these targets. At a minimum, three fusion monsters are necessary in this build: Albion the Branded Dragon requires Fallen of Albaz and a light monster. It should come as no surprise to anyone that this becomes incredibly easy to make if an opponent drops Nibiru after you have brought out Spheres. Nibiru tributes Spheres, triggering the effect of the latter and bringing out Fallen of Albaz. Since Nibiru the Primal Being is itself a light monster, Albaz can use the Nibiru summoned to your opponent's side of the field as fusion material for Albion. Albion's effect is stupid broken, especially in this deck. On summon, Albion can summon a level-8 or lower fusion monster from the extra deck by banishing fusion materials listed on the target from the hand, field or graveyard. In other words, so long as you have a Buster Blader in-hand, on the field or in the graveyard, Albion can make Buster Blader, the Dragon Destroyer Swordsman without ever needing to resolve Destruction Sword Memories in the grave. Borreload Furious Dragon, however, is an equally useful target in this build. For one, if Albaz is summoned while Buster Dragon is on the field, any dark monster on your opponent's side becomes a dark dragon-type monster, allowing Albaz to use it as material. This comes up occasionally, although Furious is more typically a follow-up fusion summon off of Albion's effect. This is Dragon Link--you're never going to have a hard time coming up with 2 dark dragons to banish as materials from the hand, field or grave. Furious itself has a useful quick effect, which allows it to pop a card on your opponent's side of the field by popping 1 monster you control. Sprind the Irondash Dragon--sadly, a machine-type and not a dragon as its name suggests--has a fine effect itself, which allows it to move to a column during the player's main phase and destroy all face-up cards in the column. This can prove useful, but its real virtue is its astonishingly simple summoning requirement: Fallen of Albaz + 1 Effect Monster Special Summoned this turn. Sprind becomes the miscellaneous Albaz fusion target off of Spheres' effect since most monsters summoned on your opponent's turn meet the criteria. Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon, for instance, would generally negate Spheres' bounce effect, but since Spheres tributes itself for cost, Fallen of Albaz will special summon from the deck--and as long as Dragoon was brought out that same turn, Albaz can fuse it and himself off for Sprind. Additional fusion targets come up, like the ubiquitous Starving Venom Fusion Dragon and even Titaniklad the Ash Dragon. Albion, Titaniklad and Sprind all have end-phase graveyard effects too, which search or recycle Fallen of Albaz and/or related spells (Branded in White, for example). Even as we anticipate the release of even better Albaz fusion targets in next year's structure deck, the basic lineup available today still works remarkably well in Dragon Link. Tech Since Artifact Lancea is such a powerful hand trap in this format, Artifact Dagda makes a lot of sense in the extra deck--and by extension, so does Artifact Scythe x1 in the main deck. I could see substituting this out since it more or less constitutes just another way to lock the opponent out of the extra deck--something that Dragon Buster Destruction Sword does already when equipped. For now, I've found it useful as a redundancy in the event that the Buster lock gets disrupted. Halqifibrax would make for a solid substitute since it can tutor out Dragon Buster Destruction Sword with its effect, though I've found I rarely went this route in building the initial board. At any rate, Protector Whelp can send it to the graveyard too for Buster Dragon to equip to a Buster Blader on your opponent's turn. Red Reign x2 probably looks a lot more gimmicky than it really is in this deck. For one, both DLink and Buster decks are making synchro monsters as part of their end boards, meaning its rare that the card cannot activate. We're also running Trap Trick x2, which can search and set a copy of Red Reign. If I open with Prologue and Trap Trick, Red Reign is the target. With Buster Dragon on the board, along with at least 1 level-8 fusion, Red Reign will banish all monsters except those with the highest level. The surviving monsters are unaffected by card effects other than their own for the remainder of the turn, which prevents your opponent from breaking your Buster lock. Since link and xyz monsters have no level, they are banished by default--something I've used to devastating effect against Tri-Brigade. It's also recyclable from the graveyard with the summon of a level-8 dark dragon synchro-monster, which comes up in a grind game from time to time. As busted as Red Reign plays in this deck though, it only narrowly edged out Gravity Collapse, which I've included in the side deck at x2. Tim Rokov's videos on this deck and other similar builds utilizing Fallen of Albaz go into greater detail on the potential combo lines, and I'll end by reiterating my props to The Wiseguys TCG YouTube channel. I suspect that as Fallen of Albaz sees greater play in meta-competitive decks over the year to come, Dragon Link players will start to experiment with and incorporate Albaz and his many draconic forms into the deck that never dies.

deck_excerpt: Why isn't Sanctuary in the Sky an option for a thumbnail?
deck_description: Buckle up kids, today I bring to you one of the strangest decks in Yu-Gi-Oh (of course not on par with the likes of the Psi-Blocker loop and the 93-step Inzektor FTK) in which you use Counter Trap cards to both gain advantage and floodgate your opponent out of the game.  The undisputed star of Counter Fairies is Bountiful Artemis. This final stage of zombie-camel evolution is from a time before every draw effect needed a once-per-turn clause attached to it. But, this is honestly needed for the deck to even stand a chance against any semi-competent deck. Without the ability to regain the advantage you lose by using all of your Counter Traps, you would be completely beaned after a single turn. Run 3 of this card every time you even think of building this deck.  The next star of the show is Guiding Ariadne. Do you remember playing a game of Yu-Gi-Oh and having the internal debate that all players have at one point in their lives where you asked yourself if activating Solemn Judgment was going to be worth the 4000 lifepoints to activate? Well now you don't have to worry. Ariadne just straight up removes the cost of most Counter Traps, letting you activate all 9 Solemns in one game and even a full playset of Seven Tools alongside it.  The final main-deck monster is Sacred Arch-Airknight Parshath. That mouthful of a card really shouldn't be played at more than one. You may look at his summoning condition and yell at me for not including a few more fairies, but to that I say: "Have you read Rebirth of Parshath?" And hell, if you're in a tight spot you can still summon him the regular way. I'd just rather not banish my Artemis for a bungus if possible.  The rest of the deck is really self-explanatory. Pot of Extravagance, Pot of Duality, and Card of Demise help you dig for your Artemis turn 1. Sanctuary in the Sky and Sanctum of Parshath both turn on Divine Punishment. Terraforming is just here so you can deck thin a smidgen. And then the Counter Trap suite is all up to preference. I do recommend at least having the three Solemns, Divine Punishment, and Rebirth of Parshath. The rest are all variable, and some other solid options not found in the main or side deck are Black Horn of Heaven, Trap of Board Eraser, Spell Vanishing, Ultimate Providence, and Judgment of Anubis. Do not play Grand Horn of Heaven. Trust me, I tried. The card sounds super cool in practice, but it can't negate a summon that does not start a chain, restricts you to only the main phase, and completely shits itself if your opponent drops Prosperity or Extrav (Ya know, two really good cards that most decks run if they can afford it).  The side deck is just to cover your weak spots. Gameciel does what it has always done and just schlorps up a problem boss monster. Heavy Storm Duster pops backrow and dodge's Imperial Order (which this deck really doesn't care about). Lost Sanctuary is just another copy of Sanctuary that can maybe negate an effect once in a while. To be honest, you can just cut this and run one of the Counter Traps I listed above instead. Seven Tools of the Bandit is just if you really really need to stop traps from activating. And Cursed Seal of the Forbidden Spell is for killing any Pacifis players dreams of playing the game of Yu-Gi-Oh.  This deck can also run Lord of the Heavenly Prison, which is just a really good card to have in backrow decks. Realistically, you were never losing to backrow removal anyway with your 9 spell/trap negates and 12 monster effect negates, but it's still nice to have a 3k beatstick to close out games. You can also run Prosperity if you really want to dig for the exact card you need. I personally think it's better to get a quick draw 2 in this deck than an extra set of Dualities, but that's just my preference. Another card that pops up in Counter Fairy lists is Van'Dalgyon the Dark Dragon Lord. This card is terrible, but also extremely funny to resolve. Run it if you're a braver man/woman/everything else in between and outside than I. You can also put actually decent cards in the Extra Deck as well. Realistically you'll never have enough monsters to make a spooky Link or Xyz board, but if you really wanna try and make combo Counter Fairies a reality, I won't crush your dreams.
I only replaced Invoked for Springans and this is the result.        GLHF

"""Main Deck  Odd-Eyes Arc Pendulum Dragon is fine at two because its searchable with Beyond and Revolution Dragon and its better to have 2 Arc Pendulum and 3 Revolution because if you need Darkwurm or Persona instead Revolution is a more versatile card to have drawn. Dragonpit is at one to deal with floodgates like summon limit or mystic mine and its also very searchable with Pendulum Call and Duelist Alliance to search out Pendulum call. Dharma-Eye is just the best Level 7 Scale 3 or lower Magician Pendulum Monster, giving destruction protection to all of your Magicians for a turn when you Pendulum summon making, it in my opinion, better than the obscure Xiangke and situational Dragoncaller but its effect doesn't come up too often so feel free to substitute it for any of the other two or even another Dragonpit. Gate Zero is at 2 so that your Darkwurm and Dragon Shrines + Foolish Burial are live even if you draw into one copy and its ok to open because its a good scale and useful level for making Absolute. Chronograph is one of your nine starters and its pretty versatile, being useable as a scale 8 and getting you a level 3 magician to make Dawn Dragster if you haven't got the resources to spare for a Celestial. Persona is at one as a low scale to be searched out with Revolution Dragon and a good target for Hieratic if you brick and can't make a full board, its also useful to bring out turn 3 as another negate by searching it out with Skullcrobat. Speaking of Skullcrobat I would run it at three if it were unlimited because its an amazing Stratos-Like Effect that searches your entire deck and its just a shame that is good scale of 8 is hampered by that restriction stopping you from summoning any Supreme King Monsters with it, its the card you want to add off Celestial for follow up plays next turn. Darkwurm comes up a bit too much at three so two is fine to keep your Dragon Shrines live and Still normal summon it occasionally and Darkwurm is at its best if you discard it as the cost for Pendulum Call to then summon it back and essentially go +3, gaining a card on field and a card in hand as well as fetching a Harmonizing to Pend summon later and get its +1 effect. Performapal Celestial Magician is the best scale 8 to end on and you will always want to pend summon it or normal summon it to make Beyond rather than summoning it from deck with Harmonizing so that you can add a Skullcrobat in the end phase. Curtain Raiser needs a reprint and will probably never get one because Konami hates Pends and it serves as the worst starter that you are forced to play because since Astrograph was banned we are in need of more Pends with Special summon effects to use to make Beyond. Harmonizing Magician is amazing and you will usually want to try to use it to summon Dragonpit to make absolute and then tune it with Celestial or if you must because of a bad hand tune it with Timegazer to make Dawn Dragster. Timegazer is a one of garnet that's is absolutely terrible to draw and is only here to be summoned off of Chronograph as a starter. Allure of Darkness is a staple in any deck running DARK Monsters and if you haven't noticed all but two of our main deck Monsters are DARK so run three. Dragon Shrine is the best starter because dumping Darkwurm is great and probably better than Chronograph because its just a more useful type of card advantage than extra spellcasters with bad levels. Duelist alliance is essentially more copies of Pendulum Call and if you already have a Pend Call you can search Arc Pendulum, its also fine to open multiple cos you can search with one then discard the second to activate Pend Call. Foolish Burial is just another Dragon Shrine. Pendulum Call is amazing and I will never run less than three in any deck I ever make ever, you can discard Darkwurm for good advantage and a starter or just discard another card that you opened too many of or isn't live at the moment and it has a neat interaction with celestial where if you use Celestials Pendulum Effect it won't be able to destroy itself but the effect can still resolve. Upstart Exists, always play one in every deck ever unless its a burn deck.  Extra Deck  Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon is easily the best Odd-Eyes Monster being able to shuffle back you previously used Pendulums to Negate anything except a Spell/Trap that activates from the GY, I usually put it in defense position because 3k is pretty good and you can always switch its position next turn. Zeus is hilarious to make going second and the best way to make it is with Utopia int Utopia Prime attack into 4-Material Zeus in MP2. Absolute Dragon is a key combo Piece that you use to make a three material Apolluosa with Beyond and another random Monster meaning it will then float into a vortex as soon as it hits the GY, its other effect is pretty nice to being able to bring back an Arc Pendulum if it negates an attack. Utopia the Lightning is good for Bonking stuff like Dragoon to death and dealing game damage if your opponent is low. Utopia Prime has an effect that might go off like once ever and is mainly a stepping stone to get Lightning and Zeus to 4 materials. Same goes for the regular No. 39. Dark Rebellion is great for doing massive damage and is just fun to use. I've been leaning more towards Adamancipator Risen - Dragite as my ending Level 8 Synchro because you can revive it with Celestial and we already have quite a few Monster Negates so I think it may actually be better to run than Savage Dragon in this deck. Ignister Prominence is the best sort of removal ever and is good to use later game as spot removal, the summon ability is ok so play a single Luster or Master Pendulum if you feel like it. Clear Wing is this decks only board wipe and it also has a pretty good Construct-like effect to destroy before damage calc so its good to have as an option. Dawn Dragster is a good Level 7 to make if you have a Timegazer in your extra deck and one level 7 when you search Harmonizing with Beyond but you don't have any Level 4 Magicians to make Savage/Dragite. Apollousa is possibly the best unbanned/unerrated link 4 in the game and it shows, you wanna make it with Beyond, Absolute and whatever random starter you have left to give it 2400 ATK and still have enough monsters to make a Level 7/8 Synchro, if you can afford it then maybe Unchained Abomination or a Borrel Link 4 would do as a substitute. Beyond the Pendulum is Insane, it searches out any combo piece and has a really good boardbreaking effect that is incredibly easy to chainblock with Harmonizing Magician or Darkwurm, its nuts and I am super Hyped for Dimension Force. Hieratic seal is the last resort option to make if you brick with no starters, get out four monsters, make an absolute then make a Hieratic with the Absolute to get vortex and then when you use Hieratic, summon Persona Dragon is defense position.  Side Deck  this side deck is pretty broad for going against loads of different decks and its also a bit pricey. Sphere Mode is fucking bullshit and if you're willing to give up your normal summon basically any board is toast before it, maybe replace it with a Kaiju if its to expensive. Lava Golem is cheap and is basically a slightly worse sphere mode that still packs one hell of a punch being able to tribute two monsters is still enough to break a lot of boards. Dark Ruler No More, its really great in in this deck fits better than Droplet, Book of Eclipse is an ok alternative if you can't afford a playset of DRNM. D Barrier is possibly one of the most unfair cards that's still legal and since the current Meta is basically free of tribute and Link archetypes aside from Flunders its incredibly lethal to flip as soon as you recognize what deck your opponent is playing. Lastly Judgement is still such a strong card and can stop enemy DRNM or an important summon so yeah pretty good for such ancient card and its always live even if you're at 1 LP.'''  I'll try to list a YouTube video of how to do the main combo at some point if I remember or someone comments telling me too. Also please Konami free our beloved Astrograph and Electrumite and maybe even Monkeyboard if you're feeling generous.

deck_excerpt: A pretty balanced Tenyi control build for the Common Charity format.
deck_description: Here is the deck I've been testing for Konami's new Common Charity format. It's a hybrid Tenyi build that focuses on some elements of control but also works to swarm the field with monsters while generating a decent hand advantage. To start, we play three Ashuna, three Vishuda, two Nahata, two Mapura, two Shthana, and two Adhara, this makes up the core of our Tenyi build. for those of you who don't know all of the Tenyi monsters have the effect to summon from hand, swarming the field so as long as you control no effect monsters, however, while they're in your hand or grave they're secondary effect comes into play. While you control even one Non-Effect monster Ashuna can summon a Tenyi from deck, Vishuda can banish from hand or grave and target a card your opponent controls returning it to the deck, Nahata can banish to reduce an opponent's monsters attack by 1500, Mapura can negate a card that target's one of your Non-Effect monsters, Shthana can reborn one of your Non-Effect monsters that was destroyed by battle or card effect, and Adhara can add one of your banished Tenyi monsters back to your hand. For the rest of the deck we play two Lava Golem to stop your opponent from gaining too strong a field, two Mimicking Man-Eater Bug, that when face down, you are still able to summon Tenyi monsters and when attacked or flipped will target a monster your opponent controls, destroy it, gain that monsters original attack and type, and has the bonus of not being able to be destroyed by monsters with the type you just acquired. In addition, we also run two Battle Fader and three Threatening Roar to stop your opponent from attacking. Two Droll and one Veiler as the hand traps, a Called By to fill your grave with a Tenyi not in hand, and finally, we're running two Vessel for the Dragon Cycle to add a Wyrm to hand. Two Lightning Vortex, two Blackout and a Pank for removal, one Reborn, one Terraforming, and one Metaverse for obvious reasons and one copy of Flawless Perfection of the Tenyi, what is essentially a pot of greed every time your opponent special summons an effect monster, and it makes your Non-Effect monsters unaffected by monster effects. For the extra deck, we have three Monk of the Tenyi and one Lanphorhynchus, easy link fodder for your main deck Tenyi's. Two Shaman of the Tenyi to bring back a Wyrm from grave. One Ra'Ten and one Sahasrara to help flood the field. Two Berserker of the Tenyi to act as a Non-Effect beat stick. One Yazi for the synchro, one Tornado Dragon for spell and trap removal, one Borreload just in case, and one World Chalice Almarduk for destruction. The final spot is filled by one Defender of the Labyrinth it can bring back a Non-Effect when it's destroyed, boost Non-Effects attack by 500, lower's effect monster attack by 500. The side is pretty self-explanatory, Lancea, Ash, and Veiler are all great hand traps. Dark ruler shuts down monster effects, an extra Flawless Perfection if you really need to draw it. Two Fists of the Unrivaled Tenyi for negation and possible summons, and two Dragon Cycle for searching and summoning. There's no perfect end board for this deck it's built to adapt and change with games not to OTK your opponent. For the most part, you want to focus on link climbing and spamming with your main deck Tenyi's, setting up a board that has two or three Non-Effect monsters like Monk or Berserker and a few Tenyi's in the grave. You'll want to rely on the disruption this deck provides by using the Tenyi's, Man-Eater Bugs, and Droll's to stop your opponent from comboing off. After that, you can set up with a Vanity's Fiend to prevent special summoning or a Lava Golem on your opponent's side with a Battle Fader in hand or Threatening Roar set to stop their battle phase and rack up some burn damage. There are a few pros and cons to this Deck I've noticed so far. Pro's: there's a lot of negates and effects in this deck to help you in turn two, it's flexible with what cards can be exchanged from the side deck, and has a lot of removal power against your opponent, and this build plays fairly well through most disruption. Cons: It's only ok going second, it's a little slow, and that pace can sometimes lose you the game, also Gravekeeper, decks that banish your grave, and cards that prevent special summoning counters this deck pretty hard. All in all, I still feel this would be a great build for the locals scene, and a fun deck to play overall. Thanks for reading.

deck_description: This is going to be my final deck profile for 2021, and the final video I am uploading for 2021. So here it is, a Dinorphia deck profile featuring the 2 new cards revealed to be in Dimension Force. Dinorphia Rexsturm requires a "Dinorphia" Fusion monster and another "Dinorphia" monster, and Dinorphia Frenzy allows you to Fusion Summon it using a Dinorphia from your Deck AND Extra Deck as material!     Since this deck is almost nothing but Traps, your goal should always be to go first, and try to summon Kentregina or Rexsturm during your opponent's turn.     Oh, and speaking of Rexsturm, it has 2 effects. If any monsters on your opponent's field have ATK that isn't lower than your Life Points, they can't activate their effects. And during either player's turn, you can pay half your life points to make those monsters' ATK equal to your Life Points! So it's a good stun card.

Basis of this engine is using The Agent of Creation - Venus to summon a bunch of Shine Balls as fodder for extra deck summons. Combo starters are Venus, as mentioned above, & a Diviner of the Herald combo that summons Master Flare Hyperion to copy Venus' effect. After summoning Shines with these, you can replace 2 of  them with your Link-1's and use all the materials to summon Saryuja Extenders to focus on are Pot of Avarice, The Agent of Life - Neptune, & The Agent of Destruction - Venus. Main idea is to spam synchros as much as possible to draw a bunch off of Hyper Librarian (this should always be your first synchro summon if possible). Genex Ally Birdman can also be used in conjunction with Venus to bounce a Shine back to hand & resummon it so you have the levels for a 3-non-tuner Crocodragon. Good luck, don't get stunned.

Hi, I like fusions. Predaplant got some nice support, and so did Fallen of Albaz, so I slapped them together with a couple Despia, Dogmatika and Shaddoll cards and called it a day!  The main deck is just some standard stuff really. There's 2 Orphys Scorpio, 1 Darlingtonia Cobra, 1 Chlamydosundew and 1 Spinodionaea(for counters), plus 2 each of the new pends Triantis and Bufollicula and 2 Byblisp from Predaplants, along with 2 copies of Predapractice to help board presence and pull more to hand, 1 Predapruning, and the only traps are 1 each Predaplanet and Predaplanning. They have useful on board effects but also offer something while in grave, planning being a destruction and planet being another fusion card. The Shaddoll package is simple, 1 each of Wendi, Ariel, Beast, Squamata, Dragon and Hedgehog. Squamata gives you more mill, Hedgehog pulls one to hand, Wendi summons one from deck, Beast draws a card, Dragon destroys 1 Spell/Trap and Ariel banishes 3 cards from either grave, and since Shaddolls like going to grave, you'll be activating their effects a lot. I also have one copy each of Shaddoll Fusion and El Shaddoll Fusion. El Shaddoll is a target to add to hand when you Nadir Servant El Shaddoll Apkallone since you can set it and quick fuse Winda on the opponent's turn without having to discard for Super Poly. Dogmatika Ecclesia and Fleurdelis are simple staples and offer Light attribute necessary for both El Shaddoll Construct and Albion the Branded Dragon without having to use your extra deck for them. I chose to run 1 Dramaturge of Despia because I like its recursion and board presence, plus it offers a negate, and Aluber gives additional search for Branded Fusion and the other spells like Branded Opening and Despia, Theater of the Branded. The real stars of the show are 1 Springans Kitt offering even more search, and  2 Fallen of Albaz. I run 2 because I've found myself running into trouble using him in hand for a fusion, then trying to use Branded Fusion to pull from deck. There is a third(technically) by using Albion the Shrouded Dragon, but getting it into position to make it count as Albaz for a fusion has proven troublesome, so I tend to use it to send 1 Albaz to grave and swap Albion for something. The remaining cards are Foolish Burial to get Byblisp to proc, 2 Polymerization, 1 Super Polymerization(removal is always nice) 1 Raigeki, and 1 Monster Reborn. So I'm a little scrubby and I like Monster Reborn, sue me.     The Extra Deck was harder since there were so many good options I had to choose between, but I ultimately decided at base, it's purely fusions. There's so many cards that lock you into fusion only, I did a test hand and ended up with 4 of those restrictions layered on top of each other. Predaplant Ambulomelioides is EXTREMELY integral because it can be fused in hand, search a Predaplant on summon, tribute itself or another monster to then summon another one, and I like to use it to tribute another low level monster, summon Chalmydosundew, then use sundew's effect to fuse into Dragostapelia. Dragostapelia is  a very good card because it has a quick effect predator counter stack, and a continuous effect where anything with a predator counter has it's effects negated. It spreading counters so easily is very beneficial to 2 of this deck's boss monsters, Triphyoverutum and Starving Venom Predator Fusion Dragon. Triph gains attack equal to every monster with a predator counter's attack so it can skyrocket very easily with Drago, Triantis(if used for a fusion, it applies counters equal to the number of monsters you control) and Spino. In addition, once a turn, Triph can negate 1 Extra Deck summon from your opponent and destroy the monster. SVPFD on the other hand can tribute any monster with a predator counter to negate something your opponent is doing. Any card or effect (that can be responded to) is just negated, simple as that, so if you can manage Drago and SVPFD, which this deck absolutely CAN do, you get 2 negates with this combo. Chimerafflesia is an extra I added, but it's still useful because its requirements mean you can use most of the Shaddolls and a Predaplant and again, does not need to be on board! For Shaddolls, it's just Construct, Apkallone and Winda, that's really all you need. Or at least, all I've ever seen people use from Shaddoll. Construct destroying any special summoned monster in battle before damage calc, Winda locking players into 1 special summon each turn while it's on board, and Apkallone giving a search when sent to grave, and the negate on summon is a nice benefit if you do decide to summon it. I run Despia Quaeritis because it's got flexible materials, and the quick effect dropping non-fusion and low level fusion monster attacks to 0 is nice since this is a fusion deck. I also run Masquerade, the Crimsongleam Dragon because it's more options to put pressure on your opponent if you go first, causing burn for every play they make. I use 1 Albion the Branded Dragon for using with Branded Fusion to send a Dogmatika to grave, so I can then summon Lubellion with it's effect by banishing the Albaz I sent to grave and a dark monster, which then ideally leaves me a Shaddoll in hand I can discard, or one in grave that I then fuse into Construct. I've done a lot of tests on running optimal lines for this, and this gives you three fusions on board, and only needs a little grave setup prior. I have Titaniklad because sometimes damage is necessary, but it doesn't do a whole lot else other than maybe be a Nadir Servant target or even a Super Poly choice. Mirrorjade is nice for its quick effect non-targeting banish and is a good option if you don't want to make a board full of fusions and only want a couple, both Albion and Lubellion lead really nicely into it. This just leaves Starving Venom Fusion Dragon and, it's just good. Any 2 Dark monsters on field so it is a great Super Poly target to remove troublesome boss monsters like Accesscode Talker, Borrelsword Dragon, Raidraptor Ultimate Falcon, Destiny HERO Destroy Phoenix Enforcer, all sorts of nasty stuff just so happens to be Dark, and if Starving Venom gets destroyed, it'll destroy any and all special summoned monsters on your opponent's field it can.  I wanted this deck to have options, and usually, thanks to all the search, I consistently get 3+ fusions on board. Out of all the tests, maybe 5 duels I ended with 2 or fewer monsters turn one, and the remaining like, 40, i've had at least 3, most often 4 monsters on board, and this deck can even pump out a completely full board with Winda, Construct, Drago and Dramaturge.  Also pls no bulli, this is my first attempt at seriously building a deck, I've just been netdecking until now but the new support was too juicy for me to not experiment with. I don't use side decks so I just slapped in whatever.

The deck is pretty standard, nothing super crazy or out there. I feel like D-Barrier is a good option, especially with Swordsoul and Drytron kicking around right now. Floowandereeze is definitely a tough matchup though.     I don't really think that 3 copies of Secret Village is the way to go, but running the Terraforming to search it is essentially 3 copies, and can thin your deck just a little bit. I also find that Strike, while a really good card, can be too detrimental in the late-game. I know that's a sign of a bad Geist player, so feel free to flame me.     Lastly, I find that the Extra Deck monsters can be really helpful in the late game, especially if you can get to Hexstia pointing to Memorygant, so I run 2 Extrav. This decision has actually never screwed me over, at least not yet. I just find that being able to keep some stuff in the ED can help when you start getting to the grind game.     IO and Summon Limit in the Side because, I mean, ya gotta run floodgates if you wanna win. It sucks, but what can you do? I have the 3rd Extrav in the side because I needed one more card in there, and I felt like I could switch it out for the Terraforming if I really needed to.     Mostly, I'm uploading this here to more easily check the TCG Player price, not gonna lie.

deck_excerpt: Powerful ritual deck based on multiple negates "Herald of Perfection" and "Vanity's Ruler" SS Lock. Draw and several different add engines. Deck almos
deck_description: INTRODUCION:  First, does it make sense to upload a deck on old banlist? Mhh for me it has sense, the stupid banlists took us too many great monsters, combos and decks. Of course, I am not allowed to speak for the entire Yu-Gi-Oh community, but that's how my heart feels. I've been working on this deck for a long time (between 2020/2021), unfortunately the first 2021 banlist crush this deck. Of course I expected this and I was going to upload this deck earlier, but striving for perfection did not allow me finish. The name of the deck is not accidental ("Drytron & Perfection") and I hope you will see it.  Provides a very good foundation for the future decks, especially if the banlist changes accordingly.  I know I didn't show many decks this year (in fact it will be the first), but I had reasons. And I assure you that my love for Yu-Gi-Oh cards is not lost and never will be and I hope people can see this in most of my decks. I'm just a sick man, and I shouldn't be sitting at the computer for a long time. Unfortunately, building and tests a great decks (I hope they are great) sometimes takes a long time. Deck in this form is very strong and hard to stop, but judge it for yourself.  Limited to one "Cyber Angel Benten" proper was a death sentence not only for this deck but also for many ritual decks especially cooperating with Drytron archetyp. Apparently KOMANI didn't want ritual decks to spread its wings. But I know and I feel ritual decks give us many more great victories in the future not only in NO BANLIST competitions. And I know that there will be people who will like this deck very much (those who swim against the tide) and for them I do this. Ritual Monsters FOREVER ;)     DECKLIST:  Now let's move to decklist. You must remember that this deck was created in January and then it was 100% up to date. "Forbidden Droplet" - may not be needed at times when "Number S0: Utopic ZEXAL" and "True King of All Calamities" are baned. I think you could use instead 3 other cards. Triple Tactics Talent also is optional. Side deck there is only a suggestion. I wouldn't experiment with the rest deck because I think it is optimized perfectly. But it's your decision (and I would make this decision based on opponent's deck).  TACTICS: (I will try to explain it simply so that everyone can understand especially newcomers).  Going first:  Of course at the beginning we should use "Pot of Extravagance" if we have him in hand (this also applies to further cards). Next "Cyber Emergency" first effect and we add the card we need for combo (that of course will depend on what already we have in hand). We use the second effect Cyber Emergency if necessary and we can discard for example Drytron monster whose effect we can use later in GY. Next "Drytron Fafnir" we add the card we need for combo and as above. And "Preparation of Rites" and this could be a very important moment, especially if we don't have yet "Cyber Angel Benten" im hand ;) Next "Pre-Preparation of Rites" and this will be the second very important effect. And vs many hand trap, may turn out to be crucial. Remember that if your opponent has for example use 3 hand traps cards it may not be necessary much, to block him in the next round. One negate or Vanity's Ruler lock or both in the field, depending on the opponent's deck. Also, keep in mind that some of these effects can be used repeatedly in 1 turn.  It is also prudent to use "Drytron Alpha Thunban" (if we use for tribute "Cyber Angel Benten")   in such a way as to add first "Cyber Angel Benten", and then add "Herald of Perfection" using effect "Cyber Angel Benten" in GY, because "Cyber Angel Benten" we usually need it much more ( it's such a small security vs hand trap in some situations).     The tactic is very simple, consists in entering to the field: "Herald of Perfection" & "Vanity's Ruler". Enter Herald of Perfection quite quickly (to have something vs Nibiru for example or other hand traps). Drytrons effects take place in hand or in a cemetery which makes this archetype resilient. Obviously the main weapon of this deck (next to "Vanity's Ruler") are multiple negates. And so that everything has hands and feet, we introduce Vanity's Ruler & Herald of Perfection with one neat combo. By the way(during comba), we add to your hand "Vanity's Ruler" & "Eva" (to increase the number of negates +2). You can also add too hand for example: "Artifact Lancea" or "Herald of orange light" or "Herald of Green Light" etc depending on the needs. With good hands, we can also introduce strong link 4 or or higher or for example "Knightmare Cerberus" co-linked with Knightmare Phoenix for more fun from game hehe.  TIPS AND TRICKS:  There is another defense mechanism built into deck in case of cards such as "Dark Ruler No More" or "Forbidden Droplet". "Herald of Perfection" is negated, but not his cost. Therefore we can use "Herald of Perfection" and use his effect, of course we don't negate anything but the cost we will have to pay and we can use "Eva" as a cost then we use "Eva" effect to add 2 cards from the deck and we can add for example "Herald of Orange Light" vs monsters deck and use an atypical hand trap. In other situations you can also use it we just add other cards for example Herald of Green Light vs powerful spell and so on.  Going Second:  First, if they are in the field set spell/trap or continuous spell/trap (floodgates) we destroy them, we use "Harpie's Feather Duster" or "Twin... cards in side deck. And for some annoying effects I recommend good old "Evenly Matched" ;) OR/AND We mainly use links and we systematically destroying the opponent's cards (relinquished anima, Geonator Transverser, Knightmare links or Avramax), depending on the needs. And of course "Accesscode Talker" for fast OTK.  SUMMARY:  Finally, I want to thank everyone who uses my decks and over a 1,5 million users ygoprodeck who watched my decks. You have been with me since December 2019 and you were with me through a difficult 2020 year (difficult for me not through COVID). I wants to dedicate deck for Oscar B. you will forever be in our hearts BRO. Thank again and remember, play for fun, not always for win. If you always play for win you newer play for fun. And then it doesn't make sense anymore. Remember also about our younger colleagues, insults and hate this shouldn't be in the game either.  Respect and as always GL HF.              Happy New Year.

Dinorphia Rexsturm is really strong! Its the win conditon that the archtype needed! I putted a Dogmatika engine here because the deck is slow, weak at going second and because Dogmatika have some interesting interactions with dinos. One card combo: Dinorphia Frenzy. At the start of your opponent main phase- Activate Frenzy (4000LP) ~Fusion summon Dinorphia Kentregina using 1 Dinorphia monster from your extra deck and another from you main deck ~Chain Kentregina quick effect to copy Frenzy effect (2000LP) ~Fusion summon Rexsturm using 1 Dinorphia from the extra deck and 1 from the main deck ~Now in the next time you activate a Dinorphia effect your life will be 1000,500 and so on, also Rexsturm will be negating passively almost all your opponent monster effects (to negate Verte Anaconda you gonna need at lest one more Dinorphia effect). Keep im mind that Rexsturm also has a quick effect to make your opponent monsters atk equal your LP, so having less LP is aways a win=win. You can summon Ultimate Conductor Tyranno in the first turn using Dogmatika Maximus effect to send 2 dinosaurs from your extra deck to the gy. Aka Nadir Servant+Ultimate Conductor Tyranno.   Notes: Floodgates dont work is this deck, except maybe for Summon Limit, but that just slows the deck even more. Imperial Order, Extinction on Schedule, Solemn Strike and other traps with burn effects aren't worth using. Just no kill yourself. After reaching 1 LP you will stop losing LP from your divisions but the effect of them still can be used. This also means that is impossible to Rexsturm to negate 0 atk monsters. Performage Damage Juggler is good to not let you die to battle or effect damage. Performage Hat Trick can be used against burn decks or if you need to xyz summon when going second. Hey Duelists of the Internet! This is my very own Satellarknight Zefra list!  It's mainly an XYZ spam deck that seeks to control the board with Triverr while also increasing consistency through a Zefra engine, all while accruing advantage through redundant search effects or bounce effects.  While this deck isn't the most competitive deck on the planet, it is incredibly fun to play, so I thought I'd share it with you all! THE ENGINES; The Zefra cards serve 3 purposes: 1) to prove scales to more easily assemble the necessary materials for a Tellarknight XYZ monster while still triggering main deck Tellarknight monster effects, 2) to increase consistency through Zefraath, Oracle and Providence by either searching up Pendulum Scale pieces or searching other Tellarknight monsters (Zefraxciton and Zefrathuban) for XYZ plays, and 3) to provide a going-first control package with Zefraniu, Nine Pillars, Divine Strike, and War.  Zefraath is a key card here - I've never actually summoned it since you only want it in the Pendulum Scale.  It allows us to dump a Zefra monster (usually Zefraniu going first and later Zefrathuban or Zefraxciton for extending plays) to the extra deck to copy that monster's Pendulum Scale rating.  Assuming we have the opposite Scale set as well, we'll be able to Pendulum Summon that monster; however, since Zefraath's normal Scale is 5, it is very easy to Pendulum Summon our Tellarknight monsters if this effect doesn't go through. The main deck Tellarknight cards provide consistency, either by searching Scales or follow-up cards with Deneb, dumping Tellarknight monsters in grave with Unukalhai, or by recurring Tellarknight monsters in grave for XYZ plays with Altair.  Vega is good for extending if our Scales don't survive our opponent's turn (although they should due to Providence's in-grave effect) while Alsham gives us access to burn damage if the game is running into time, or we just need an easy finisher.  Keep in mind that all these effects trigger if the Tellarknight monster is Summoned - not just Normal or Special Summoned, but also Pendulum Summoned (hence the value of the Zefra engine). The extra deck Tellarknight cards are how we win the game.  We usually want to win with Triverr, since it bounces every card on the field other than itself, then let's us discard a card from our opponent's hand, essentially letting us dismantle our opponent's board while (hopefully) discarding any cards they could use for a follow-up play. The hidden power of Triverr is in bouncing our own cards to the hand.  Our board, usually being Oracle of Zefra and Pendulum cards in the Scales, is easily rebuildable, plus we can get repeated activations from a single copy of Oracle, allowing us to set up for next turn.  Plus, Triverr brings back a Tellarknight monster if it's destroyed.  Delteros is spot removal that can float if destroyed while providing protection for us when we Summon monsters.  Constellar Diamond is easy to go into and is a floodgate on a stick against certain decks that want to dump things to the grave or recur cards from the grave to the hand.  The negation effect doesn't always come up, but when it does, it is very powerful.  Batlamyus is there to get us into these three monsters easier if we only have 2 Tellarknight monsters to summon. OTHER CARDS: Ash Blossom and Imperm are here for negations - feel free to change these to adapt to your meta as you see fit. Terraforming and RotA are here for more consistency - we want to see Oracle, and RotA can grab almost every one of our main deck monsters. Satellarknight Skybridge - an interesting tech that I like to run.  Essentially swaps a Tellarknight on field with a Tellarknight in deck, which is useful if we need to get some advantage from a monster about to be destroyed or if we draw a dead Tellarknight monster and want something more useful.  Just remember you're locked into summoning Tellarknight monsters for that turn.  Could be shaved/replaced for some of the other cards in the "Things I've Been Messing With" section. The Link Monsters - Gravity Controller is here to get rid of a monster stuck in the extra monster zone (usually a Pendulum Summoned monster), clearing it out for another Pendulum Summon if need be.  It doesn't come up every game, but you'll definitely love the card when it does come up.  I:P, Unicorn, and Borrelsword are good value cards/finishers in the deck, and are easy to make since we can spam lots of monsters. Abyss Dweller, Bagooska, and Gallant Granite - These are just good XYZ monsters for the deck.  Dweller is a floodgate and really hurts some decks, Bagooska buys us time if we brick, and Granite can search up Zefraath. LINES OF PLAY There aren't really any set combos in the traditional sense here; rather, the deck is consistently trying to get to certain end goals.  Whichever way you do that is dependent on what's in your hand.  Usually, you want to get you Scales set up and have some sort of play for next turn. So for example, take the following hand: [Deneb, Zefrathuban, Providence, Ash Blossom, and Alsham]. If we are going first, we could search Oracle with Providence, play Oracle, grab Zefraath, activate Zefraath and Zefrathuban in the Scales, activate Zefraath sending Zefraniu, Pendulum Summon Zefraniu and Deneb, search with Zefraniu and Deneb, grab Nine Pillars and Altair, Normal Summon Alsham, burn for 1000 then XYZ summon Bagooska or Dweller. If we are going second, we could search Oracle with Providence, play Oracle, grab Zefraath, activate Zefraath and Zefrathuban in the Scales, activate Zefraath sending Zefraxciton, Pendulum Summon Zefraxciton and Deneb, grab Altair, Normal Summon Alsham, burn for 1000 then XYZ summon Triverr, bouncing the field and giving us a second Oracle activation next turn in addition to Altair as a follow-up. In both these examples, the important thing was setting the Scales - you usually want to do this if you can.  However, after this, we had a lot of branching pathways to get to different end boards depending on what we want to end our turn on.  This high degree of searchability is one of the strengths of the deck. THINGS I'VE BEEN MESSING WITH: To date, I've been playing around with some different packages/techs for the deck: Utopia Package:  This is Number 39: Utopia, Number 39: Utopia Double, and Double or Nothing.  This is an alternate finisher for the deck.  Summon Utopia Double with two materials, then detach a material to add Double or Nothing from deck to hand and special Utopia onto Utopia Double, doubling Utopia's attack.  Then, you attack a monster with Utopia (since you can't attack directly due to Utopia Double's effect), negate the attack with Utopia, activate Double or Nothing, then attack again for massive damage.  I cut this due to lack of room in the extra deck, but it is a fun combo that I may try again later in the future. King of the Sky Prison:  This is the addition of King of the Sky Prison and 2 Call of the Haunted.  Essentially, you go into Gallant Granite to search King, activate King, then pass the turn.  On the opponent's turn, you activate a Set card (usually Nine Pillars or Divine Strike), Special Summon King, then Set any extender/searcher you may need from the deck for next turn.  If you go into Triverr next turn, you can bounce the King and do it again next turn!  This one is pretty fun to pull off. CLOSING REMARKS: Hopefully this guide gives you a decent look into playing this deck.  As I've said before, it's not the most competitive deck out there, but it's really fun to play and is surprisingly more resilient than you might expect. Thanks for taking a look at my build, and good luck with your duels!

deck_excerpt: Ideas about this version of the deck I want to share
deck_description: About Evil★Twin core the biggest difference I see between decklists is that you only use 2 Live☆Twin Ki-sikil and opt for the second copy of Live☆Twin Ki-sikil Frost which is something you can test. The Dogmatika engine is simple and effective and brings nice synergies with the archetype because as you use Evil★Twins Ki-sikil & Lil-la then you can simply send an Evil★Twin's Trouble Sunny to the gy and use it as a removal opponent's cards even if you don't control any Evil★Twin monster. It's also because of the Dogma engine that I've decreased the number of Link-2 Evil★Twin in the extra deck. On other decklist choices: What do I think of Crossout Designator? Crossout is a bad vibes card in the sense that it does the same thing as Called By the Grave but worse for the need to use targets that need to be in your deck and I believe that not any deck can use it because it benefits a lot decks that have room for multiple tech cards like this one but not decks that have a very small space so it's better to focus on using other cards. Speaking of main deck targets, Nibiru is the main one because there are no ways to play around it with this archetype and only use 1-off because Nibiru conflicts with Evil★Twin's and this problem has already cost me games so I don't find one Very good card to use and I already have two bricks which are the main deck Evil★Twins and Fleurdelis and I don't want this number to increase. Another caveat I want to make is the use of Enemy Controller because it is a budget option for the Forbidden Droplet but if you have the Droplet I recommend using it without thinking twice because it excels in this deck and makes your Crossout Designator much better . About the extra deck I see that many players don't use Sky Cavalry Centaurea but rather the Gachi Gachi Gantetsu and I think its use is due to a budget option because Sky Cavalry is much better in the role of accessing AA-Zeus by the factor of be able to bounce an opponent's monster in the battle phase and there are monsters like Lyrilusc - Ensemblue Robin that you don't want to send to the GY at all, but banish or return to the extra deck. Another card that is not used much is the Linguriboh which in this version has the fundamental role of versus Tri-Brigade you have the Normal Summon of a Live☆Twin Ki-sikil for example denied and then you do Linguriboh to negate the Tri-Brigade Revolt and then Next you activate Nadir Servant to clear the rest of the opponent's field. Regarding the Side Deck one change I would make would be to use PSY-Framegear Gamma package. Regarding spell/trap removal I like the 7 used and Red Reboot is justified in this deck because you have very easy access to AA-Zeus of 4 materials so you will hardly get punished for using Red Reboot and not getting all of your opponent's traps of field. These are all the ideas I bring with this decklist for you to make changes.

deck_excerpt: (Albaz after punching the meta in the crotch) "The Fusion is now Old Man". This framework of deck aims to use the upcoming branded fusion engine to ea
deck_description:
This deck is a work in progress to test the branded fusion with Witchcrafters; this will probably not be meta relevant in the slightest, so if you are interested in a more pure variant of the build I uploaded one earlier in December. For this reason also, the ratios may not be the most optimal and I'm happy to hear any feedback on this build in the hopes of improving this build once it arrives in the TCG.
Choice of cards in the main deck explained:  -A lot of Spellcasters, literally half the deck (20/40) consists of spellcasters including the handtraps. 10x Witchcrafter monster cards (I go more in depth with them in my pure build #shameless_plugin)  +  8x Witchcrafter spell cards. Good hands are when you don't open Haine and Verre, lucking illusion of chaos the new inclusion can fix your hand while also providing you with a starter. The most ideal opening start would be to open the Branded Fusion, this card would fusion summon Albion the branded dragon which on summon can allow you to fusion summon Witchcrafter Vice-master by banishing the required material from GY/hand or field. To summon Albion, you send Fallen of Albaz + 1 Light monster, by sending a light Witchcrafter you can satisfy 1/2 the required materials for Vice-master. Once Vice-master is on the field, you can activate its effects and setup your field, the only restriction the Branded Fusion causes is not allowing you to special summon from the Extra Deck except Fusions, so nothing too harsh. Ideally you want to end your board with either Witchcrafter Haine as your (psuedo-Drident) and/or Witchcrafter Madame Verre for disruption.  -Ash blossom& joyous spring, as a hand-trap, remains the most popular option of choice for its versatility, but I choose to cut for both Effect Veiler and Droll & Lock Bird as viable options, especially in the current meta; they also are favored for being spellcasters. Psy-Framegear Gamma + Psy-Frame Driver are in the deck to make sure your spells go through and the activated effects of the Witchcrafters card are not negated. In case of a disruption on your turn, we have a single copy of Called by the grave and 2 copies of Triple Tactics Talent for recovery and follow-up. -Magicians' Souls + Illusion of Chaos, are a compact package that allows you to thin the deck/fix your hand/and draw cards with souls, this engine can be made more consistent with the inclusion of Preparation of Rites. [Beginner Tip: Illusion of chaos can place itself on the top of the deck in a pinch, but keep in mind once you special summon souls, you send from deck to GY and then shuffle.] That should make the main deck clear, honestly learning to play well with the Witchcrafter portion of the deck is probably the most important thing for its success, just to give you the main idea, you want to blink from any Witchcrafter > Schmietta > Genni > ending on either Witchcrafter Haine or Witchcrafter Madame Verre. In the GY, Schmietta can send any Witchcrafter spell card for Genni to copy its effect: [Best card to use with Genni in GY is  Witchcrafter confusion for a fusion summon/ Witchcrafter Holiday for recovery / Witchcrafter Creation to fetch Golem Aruru to hand for disruption]. If only Schmietta is in grave the best thing to probably send by its GY effect is probably Bystreet, for protection. Draping is for specifically countering Imperial Order, but it can be used for multiple other targets that may come up.
Extra Deck: -Fusion line-up: of 6 Fallen of Albaz fusion targets and 2 of the vice-master herself, the ratios can be adjusted and experimented with this is what I am comfortably running currently. Albion the Branded dragon is what you summon off of branded fusion going first, as this almost always guarantees successfully summoning vice-master. If you feel like high rolling, Lubellion the Searing Dragon is your target by sending Haine/Illusion of Chaos and Albaz to GY, activate Lubellion's on summon effect to discard one LIGHT monster from hand specifically to special summon Albion the Branded which will banish the Haine and Albaz to give you Vice-master, and ending with 3 monsters on field. [NOTE: you are locked from summoning from the Extra deck only fusion monsters.] -1 level 8 synchro monster: this can basically be any monster as it seldom comes up, but the theory behind Psy-Framelord Omega is that it allows you recover your banished cards. The only way to make this monster is with Gamma + Driver, but you maybe don't wanna make a synchro summon at all as it conflicts with Branded Fusion's summoning condition. -Link line-up: Artemis, the Magistus allows you to send any Witchcrafter normal summon to the grave when you want to activate their graveyard effects but don't want to ditch a spell, that is basically the limit of its function. Predaplant Verte Anaconda is an auto inclusion to most decks that fusion summon these days, however we are not using it nefariously to summon DPE or Dragoon, but to access Vice-masters by using either Witchcrafter confusion or Magicalized fusion. Branded fusion is a terrible option with this monster as you can't special summon at all afterwards. This monster is also very helpful with Super polymerization. Lambda, is to allow you to use Psy-Framegear gamma in hand when you have an already established field consisting of monsters. Halqifibrax > Selene > Accesscode talker OTK. This combo can be made with any 2 monsters including a tuner, currently only effect Veiler but you can steal a tuner with Triple tactics talents if needed, this allows you summon effect veiler from deck and then link climb into a link-3 Selene, that special summons the same effect veiler from GY or any spellcasters you have really; Link climb again into Accesscode talker with 5300 attack and 2 pops on the field. [Tip: Accesscoder made this way will have 5300 atk + 2700 atk that vice-master has will = 8000 LP] GG EZ.
Side deck options for going second:
  • 3x Dark ruler no more
  • 3x Super polymerization + at least 2 targets
  • 3x Nibiru, the rock
  • 3x Artifact Lancea
  • 3x Evenly Matched
  • 1x Harpie's feather duster
  • 1x Magician's Left Hand/ Magician's Right Hand [tip: these cards can stop super-poly/dark ruler no more/evenly match]
  • 1x Rank-8 of choice
PROS: The branded engine adds consistency and power, while the pure variant plays a slower control style of build, this deck is more aggressive and combo oriented. Illusion of chaos is basically additional copies of magicains' souls which almost always found place in the deck. Going second, people have few answers to super polymerization and dark ruler no more, essentially you can go for an OTK almost all the time. The playstyle of the deck is essentially vice-master turbo, the card is a house, it's function is to stop your opponent from making a board to counter yours, Haine supports vice-master by target protection, Golem Aruru protects it from battle, and bystreet protects it from destruction. The rest of the tools in the deck are for consistency and to ensure you end on Vice-master. CONS: This deck relies heavily on vice-master which in itself, lacks built-in protection and negates. Also it losses heavily to the sideboard. Even though Albaz adds a lot to the deck, it is much more stronger in other decks that build powerful turn one negates. Witchcrafters, even though I love them a lot, minus a lot with their current mechanic; which while it is interesting playstyle, stops it from ever reaching meta status.

The return of Tellarknights ... while the archetype does need new support it's still able to keep up with the meta with the likes of hand trap, traps, super poly targets and having a small DPE engine, Triverr looping and hitting your opponent with storming mirror force can be very overwhelming and makes them waste more recourses so they can get there bored back and if you have ash, belle or super poly to counter them getting there bored back it comes hard for your opponent to gain advantage on you. The Tellarknight archetype is build to mainly counter Dark and 9/10 times should be winning that matchup, the only Dark deck in the meta right now that would be a bit of a grind game would be against PK. this deck is for a homebrew format i'm working on called Vanguard format.     The main gist of this homebrew format is that you start with a designated non-effect main deck monster on the board (either a normal monster or non-effect ritual monster) that cannot be tributed, cannot attack the opponent directly, cannot be used as the cost of another card's effect, cannot be turned face down, can't be taken control of, can switch between attack and defense position and takes damage in both attack and defense position. The concept is somewhat borrowed from Cardfight! Vanguard in that its a monster that remains on the board at all times and represents the player.     This is designed to be a multi-man format (akin to Commander in MTG), hence why i have cards like The Forceful Sentry and Painful Choice allowed despite otherwise being banned in the OCG and TCG since i feel like they do a good job of encouraging negotiations between different players since you have to first designate which opponent you'll use a card's effect on in 3+ man games.     When selecting the monsters for your main deck, you can only pick monsters that share either the same attribute and/or the same monster type as your vanguard. For example, i can put any dark and/or cyberse monsters in the main deck because Suppression Collider is a dark cyberse monster.
