deck_excerpt: Activate Fusion Destiny after they negate Branded Fusion
deck_description:
The aim of the deck is to put up interruptions with the Springans cards (Interluder, Blast, and Captain Sargus), and then support those with Mirrorjade or Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer. The most common play to make with the field spell and a Springans monster in hand is to activate Gold Golgonda, pitch the Springans monster, summon Merrymaker and depending on what you pitched with Gold Golgonda the combo can branch out: Branga
  • Send anything other that Branga to GY with Merrymaker
  • Activate Branga effect in GY banishing both Springan's monsters
  • Search Interluder or Blast as an interruption
Captain Sargus
  • Send Brothers to GY with Merrymaker
  • Activate Brothers to Summon Captain Sargus from GY
  • Activate Brothers to attach it as material to Merrymaker, giving Sargus a pop on your opponents turn
DPE is is a little more reliable than Mirrorjade at times because, going second you will most likely use Mirrorjade's banish effect which means it is just a body on your oppoenets turn. In comparison DPE can always pop cards. The advantage Mirrorjade has is its ability to send Albion from the Extra Deck to the GY to search Judgement of Stigmata or sending Sprind the Irondash Dragon which allows you search or summon a Springans or Fallen of Albaz. The deck is fully equip to go second. It features 8 hand traps. Ash and Impermanence are a must in my opinion. If you fix some of the ratios, Gamma fits well into the deck because the Springans XYZ can banish themselves on your opponents turn, leaving you with no monsters on the field which allows you to activate Gamma. Ghost Ogre can be replaced by Veiler. They are both Light meaning they can be used to summon Albion if that situation ever occurs. I chose Ghost Ogre because although it doesn't negate, it takes bodies off the field and it is useful against field spells which tend to generate advantage. Fallen of Albaz is great going second because it forces your opponent to make a decision which can bait out negates or handtraps. Furthermore, its basically the only normal summon in a deck that isn't reliant on the normal summon, so it being negated doesn't cripple the strategy. Lastly, Exblowrer is great going second if you can get material under it.

deck_excerpt: Going-2nd Build for Common Charity Gren Maju.
deck_description:
I've been a Gren Maju player since 2016. It is undeniable that the deck has come a long way - even becoming playable occasionally. Common Charity will have a good amount of competent decks that gatekeep the format - some with surprising capabilities. I believe some variation of this build of Gren Maju can keep up with the likes of "Towers" strategies (often midrange decks that "turbo" unaffected monsters with threatening stats) and control strategies, as well as assert dominance over other agro strategies (this deck's forte) DECK STRATEGY Many consider Gren Maju to be an OTK deck. Some play it as a stun variant. I Myself view Gren as a Midrange/Control Deck which incidentally can OTK, and have played it this way since Eater Of Millions became legal in the TCG. I personally feel that Gren is best suited for explosive plays, aiming to break the opponent's board (or hard-punish them for not building one on Turn 0). Gren, played in this manner, seeks to accomplish the following win condition against competent decks:
  1. Force the opponent rapidly deplete resources in the first turn(s) by mass removal and/or insane attack pressure
  2. Win in the mid-game by having higher-quality threats than the opponent
PROS
  • Gren Maju decks, if tuned properly, can reasonably break any board and have decent OTK potential.
  • This particular build blanks opposing spell/trap removal (pre sideboard), as it has no reliance on continuous backrow or field spells.
  • Played skillfully, Gren Maju also provides opportunity for technical plays that exploit the mechanical limitations of some other kinds of decks.
CONS
  • Gren Maju is inherently weak to backrow. This is offset by mass removal like Lightning storm in Advanced Format, but this weakness is pronounced in Common Charity.
  • Gren is traditionally unable to grind at a high tempo, leaving it at a disadvantage to highly recursive decks - specifically decks that can recur removal.
  • Gren Maju is at a huge disadvantage when hand size is low - despite sometimes insane top-deck draws.
  • Gren must have a plan in the side deck to go 1st if forced to do so during a match
The biggest drawback of Gren Maju is related skill/deck-building. First of all, the deck MUST be tuned to a particular meta to be consistently effective against competent decks. This is true for any Rouge Deck. While Gren Maju Decks are fairly intuitive to play, effective deckbuilding is what enables their success. Lastly, you must be very knowledgeable about the rules of the game to be baseline effective at this deck, let alone boast a winning record on a competitive level. MAIN DECK - MONSTERS 3x Gren Maju Da Eiza Less "OTK boi" and more Removal Through Attacking and lightning-rod for certain negates and removal. Incidentally, sometimes it will result in your opponent's life points being reduced to 0, which is an added bonus. Biggest drawback to Gren is that he is not a 1-Card-Combo... He Needs an enabler to banish cards, which reduces the consistency of this deck. Nonetheless, the upsides far outweighs the downside, and its good enough to name the deck after it...   3x Eater Of Millions Depending on the Matchup, the Removal that Eater provides ranges from highly effective to just ok. This card does serve as a secondary Gren Maju, both in terms of removal through attacking and winning through damage output.   3x Necroface A tertiary Gren Maju, again serving as removal through attacking and winning through damage output. HOWEVER, this is a "non-bo" with Gren while, as well as a conflicting Normal Summon. These drawbacks are balanced with this card's synery with gold sarcophagus and enabling you to grind (sometimes indefinately). Normal Summoning Necroface may result in continued plays with Gizmek Orochi, pot of desires, etc.   3x GizMek Orochi, The Serpentine Sky Slasher Easily the best monster in the deck. It fades battle damage by soaking up an attack or simply "flashes-in" on your opponent's end phase, is spell speed 1 monster removal, and has decent stats... All while fueling Gren Maju, Eater, or Necroface. This card's  quick effect to special summon itself is very good, and its ability to destroy a face-up monster is good too (when you have the opportunity to use it).   3x Divine Serpent Geh. Easily the Worst Monster in the Deck. It is situational, costs half of your life points to use, and takes a little experience to get the feel for when it is good and what situational synergies it brings to the deck. However, it is untargetable, and can usually get over any monster your opponent controls (as long as they have not gained atk). Furthermore, it negates random things like Flip effects during the damage step when it declares an attack, as well as certain problematic continuous effects of the attack target. This card is usually really good against decks that rely on targeted removal.     In an alternate universe, this card is D. D. Assault Carrier, if that card was actually playable.   3x Radian, the Multidimensional Kaiju This card enables removing a "Towers"-like monster from the board. Its the Lowest ATK Kaiju at common rarity, and is dark too! 1X DinoWrestler Pankratops A Solid going-2nd card. Serves as removal via attacking or its own effect. The flexibility this card offers is frankly amazing, despite is lack of a dark attribute of level of 8...   1x Phantom Skyblaster Often times, this is a 1 card Link 3, which will often serve as a form of targeted monster removal and an attacker. Dark attribute is good too. It is however, the deck's 7th normal summon, which is pushes the boundary for normal summon only monsters a little bit.   1x Battle Fader It has dark dynergy and is enables counter-attack plays that can result in victory. It is outclassed by Gizmek Orochi for what it does, however. MAIN DECK - SPELLS 3x Pot of Desires A +1 in card advantage whose cost synergizes with 9 of our monsters - auto include   3x Allure of Darkness Card advantage neutral, but has has synergy Necroface, serving as a way to rip apart your opponents deck and eventually boost Gren (or another Necroface). We play 17 dark monsters, to it is sometimes viable to activate this card with no dark monsters In hand, and is rarely dead otherwise.   3x Forbidden Chalice One of the best cards in the deck. Since we kind of want the opponent to go off on Turn 0, we don't mind too much on mission out on playing Effect Veiler instead. This card also enables some combat tricks, allowing a Gizmek Orochi to attack over a Radian, a Necroface to get over a boss monster, etc. Also, on the off-chance that magic cylinder is a great card in Common Charity format, this can very well save you from your own Gren... Also good in the mirror (should that ever be a thing you encounter)   3x Dark Hole The expectation is never for this card to lead to an OTK, but is is a very good way to punish out opponents for not setting up a solid board Turn 0. Occasionally, this may blow your opponent out, but most of the time, against competent decks, this card will be part of the sequence of plays you make to attrite your opponent into the ground by the mid game.   1x Monster Reborn This card enables all sorts of situational plays. It is arguable that Upstart Goblin is better in this slot.   1x Gold Sarcophagus In a long game, ensuring that you see a Necroface eventually, can be the difference between winning and losing. Occasionally can lead to banishing some good stuff out of your opponent's deck via this play. Can also get any card in the deck if you figure it'll be good in 2 turns.   1x Called by the Grave We want to have offensive turns with this deck, relying on activated abilities of monsters and spells. This card is good at protecting against hand traps, as well as disrupting resources in the opponent's GY.   1x Foolish Burial Basically Gizmek Orochi #4. If ever make a rank 8 XYZ with this build, if will probably involve this card.   MAIN DECK - TRAPS 3x Typhoon Admittedly, this card is not as good as twin twisters of Cosmic Cyclone - or even MST in some cases. However, I don't this deck is well suited for Twin Twisters (despite Gizmek synergy), and snake-boi Divine Serpent Geh will likely cost us 4000 Life Points for its first activation, adding some risk to Cosmic Cyclone that i'd personally rather avoid. Really, this is a symptom of the bigger issue here: there are not enough playable level 8s for this deck. We would happily leave Geh behind for a competent level 8 - then we could even dump some of the sacky spell cards for Trade In! Spells enable this deck to function. Anti-Spell Fragrance and Imperial Order will prevent us from breaking a well set up board time and time again. Typhoon will always out those cards, and has situational advantages against field spell decks.  Cosmic Cyclone is in the Side deck if you really need it. EXTRA DECK 3x Linkuriboh You can make this card with Eater when situations come up where that is advantageous, so try to always leave 1 in your extra deck during gameplay. You can also make this with Battle Fader   3x Ra'Ten, The Heavenly General Phantom Skyblaster goes into this card, and then you blow something up with it. 2 of these copies are banish fodder. This card allows you to target and destroy a card at the start of the battle phase,   3x Steel Star Regulator An Objectively Worse Ra'Ten. Banish Fodder   3x Number 62: Galaxy Eyes Prime Photon Dragon Can get up to 5600 atk on its own and can serve as a situational out to certain cards, if ypou can make this rank 8 play 3x Aegaion The Sea Castum We need to banish something from the extra deck to summon Eater of Millions and it might as well be this. Can serve as a situational wall/removal, and if your opponent's extra deck is running out you might hit a payoff... or something. SIDE DECK 1x Macro Cosmos & Dimensional Fissure If you're going to be forced to go 1st, might as well play cards that make your deck better (despite lost Gizmek Value), and probably make your opponent's deck much worse.   2x Trap Trick If your going to go 1st, might as well have 2 more copies of Torrential Tribute and Banquet of Millions in your Deck   3x Torrential Tribute One of the best traps in the game and right in line with the deck's plan to induce resource depletion for the opponent. Just know your matchups so you know when to use it.   2x Banquet of Millions If forced to go 1st when wen don't want to, this matchup dependent card can ensure that we see out next turn, at which point our gameplan resumes as normal.   2x Dark Ruler No More When you know you want to go 2nd and the matchup will inevitably be a grind, or you know that your opponent's board will be very difficult to break.   3x Cosmic Syslone Useful for whenever Typoon alone is insufficient.     HOT TAKES TRADE IN So Close... If you're willing to play Schwartzchild Limit Dragon and perhaps another lv 8, you can replace Divine Serpent Geh and some spells for lv8s and some number of Trade Ins. Right now, I think Gizmek Orochi is the only Level 8 worth playing, which is a shame. Gren can't afford to sit with a dead Trade In in hand, and you don't need the ordeal of trading an optimal Gizmek play on your opponent's turn for that pseudo +1 from pitching it with trade In. We just need more playable lv8s. Of course, you do you... I'm Projecting here. POT OF DUALITY Not for me... I've never liked this card in Gren. I think Gren plays a sub-optimal stun strategy, and losing your ability to have a maximally explosive turn at any point in the game seems like an anit-synergy to me. I'd rather run something like Upstart Goblin and just hope I banish it every time...

deck_name: Therions deck,(next tier 1)Therions’ “King” Regulus, new,: D
deck_description: https://youtu.be/7t_Gmns_qdI

Incredibly fun deck that utilizes a lot of unique synchros that many other decks cannot, such as: Psychic End Punisher, Trishula Zero Dragon, Crystron Quariongandrax, and Hyper Psychic Riser. The fact that most level 8's search virtually the whole archetype makes this shockingly consistent (we're talking virtually every single game). Standard Going First Combo:
  1. Summon Sharakusai and use its effect with the 1 other punk monster you have in hand or on field to summon Carp Rising
  2.  Activate Carp Rising to summon Dia Note and Madame Spider from deck
  3. Madame Spider effect to search a Punk Trap from deck (usually Dangerous Gabu if you don't draw it)
  4. Synchro into Madame Spider and Dia Note into Dragite
  5. Dia Note effect to summon back Sharakusai in defence mode
End Board:
  1. 1 spell/trap negate with Dragite since Carp Rising in grave is a water (important to use Dragite because the deck has several monster negates but no spell/trap negations)
  2. Bounce 3 with Sharakusai effect by synchroing on opponents turn with Dragite to summon Amazing Dragon (bounce 3 since the combo ends with 3 level 3 tuners in grave)
  3. 1 monster negate and life point gain with Dangerous Gabu
  4. 3 to 4 other cards for extending into more synchros or Lambda, follow up, or additional interruptions
Pro Tip: If you can spare an e-tele, don't summon back the Sharakusai at the end of the combo so you can avoid Nibiru (you would be at 4 summons at that point). Then set the e-tele and use it on your opponents turn to summon another Sharakusai from deck to pull off the same 3 card bounce with Amazing Dragon. Going second you can also bait out a lot of interruptions and still end on Amazing Dragon to equalize the game state, if not push for game with a Psychic End Punisher and something else.
BANNED CARD

Because this archetype lacks in recover im using There Can be Only One in the main deck as a secondary win conditon. Tbh i would be more comfortable without, but it is such a good card and can steal some games alone.        GLHF

deck_excerpt: I've been working on this deck list for 2 years. Play tested against Meta, and seen lots of trial and tribulation. While it's not the best out there,
deck_description:
While the goal of this deck is to aim for a OTK, it's flexible enough to continue playing if that doesn't work out.

Going Second:

You will want to go second if shooting for OTK. General strategy is to XYZ Summon Starliege Photon Blast Dragon and Prime Photon Dragon using Galaxy-Eyes Afterglow Dragon. Detach in battle phase, and double Prime Photon's already massive ATK points.

Going First:

If going first, XYZ Summon Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord and Starliege Photon Blast Dragon (Preferably equipped with Photon Orbital, as this will make your board state very hard to deal with)  

Tips:

in case you fail to do OTK you can also summon C107 or Cipher Drago / Neo Cipher Drago or you can also summon them just to increase Prime Photon Dragon's ATK points.
Idek

Similar as the last build i posted, but the changes:
  • as i was running only 8 Resonators monsters i got a little bit of extra consistency, but ran out of resources too fast (due to desires and non-recyclable combos) so i took of 1 Chain Resonator and 1 staple in order to play 1 extra Red Resonator and Synkron Resonator. the strategy stills maximizing the chance to having Crimson Resonator in most of the plays. (3 Crimson + 3 Call + 1 Chain). obs: prosperity is way better, but it's expensive that's why i choose desires. in prosperity you can get rid of the extra resonator names.;
 
  • reduced amount of hand traps/ techs in the main deck: it's a going first combo deck, you can play with board breakers in main deck if you like, but hand traps, especially Veiler that enables chaos ruler's reborn eff, makes you play around less interactions and kill turn 2 anyway;
 
  • Inca engine good thing: makes your hand 1 card combo. bad thing: the bricks. They can be usefull sometimes when you banish some combo pieces on desires or bricked hands with them, but your play will be a lot less deeper. This engine can meke a plus 2 when you discard Red Reign to go for Chaos Ruler and recycle it;
 
  • the extra deck is kinda limited when talking about interactions (Supernova + Abyss + Void Ogre + Red Wyvern) because  the deck it locks itself in Dark Dragon Synchro. With inca engine there is sometimes you can go for Abyss + Red Wyvern, but you must choose well how to interact with your opponent. Red Reign is not searchable besides if chaos ruler can mill it nor Inca engine recycle combo, but it helps covering the interactions that extra deck can't do. You can play a second copy of Supernova as well, it's eff isn't even once per turn; FUN FACT: Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend plays around Evenly Matched.
that's it. My thought process while building this deck was keeping in mind the Virtual World ratios, its kinda similar when buildind and it's play stile sometimes is kinda similar with SwordSoul as well. Thank you!

The new Therions Regulus does wonders for ABC, it not only gives you a free negate for absolutely nothing but also extends your plays as well. So I tried it out and this is what I came up with for it.  Little ABC trivia! A assault core, B buster drake, and C crush wyvern all represent the “ABCs” of deck building with monsters, spells, and traps. A assault core represents monsters, it protects the monster it’s equipped to from monster effects, it also is the color orange to resemble the card border for monsters  B buster drake represents spells, it protects a monster it’s equipped to from spell effects and is green which is the spell card border  C crush wyvern is a trap protector and is mostly purple which is the trap border  I just put that together myself and kicked myself for not noticing a long time ago

deck_excerpt: Use Number 39: Utopia Double to summon D/D/D Duo-Dawn King Kali Yuga! Shut down your opponent for a turn and follow up with a Double or Nothing! OTK!
deck_description: Use Number 39: Utopia Double to summon D/D/D Duo-Dawn King Kali Yuga! Shut down your opponent for a turn and follow up with a Double or Nothing! OTK! Use any 2 level 4 monsters to summon Utopia Double. Ideally one of the materials should be ZS - Ascended Sage to search for The Phantom Knights' Rank-Up-Magic Launch, which will summon Kali Yuga during your opponent's turn. Set PKRUM, then enter your End Phase (to dodge Effect Veiler and Nibiru, The Primordial Being) to use Utopia Double's effect to overlay Number 99: Utopia Dragonar, then use Dragonar's effect to summon any Dark Rank 7 Number monster. On your opponent's turn, in response to any card they activate during their Main Phase (preferably on field), you can respond with PKRUM to use your Dark Rank 7 as material to Rank-Up into D/D/D Duo-Dawn King Kali Yuga! IMMEDIATELY after his XYZ summon, even in the middle of a chain, Kali Yuga will prevent the activation of new cards on the field, AND negate any cards effects currently on the field. This prevents common board breakers like Forbidden Droplet, Forbidden Chalice, even Dark Ruler No More from activating OR resolving and essentially prevents your opponent from comboing. If your opponent tries to set up backrow like Ice Dragon's Prison you can use Kali Yuga's effect to destroy ALL spells and traps on the field so that you can close the game next turn. This deck excels against combo strategies (if you can go first), but struggles against control strategies. Even with the advantage of being able to destroy backrow, the opponent can simply set Dogmatika Ecclesia, The Virtuous to prevent any OTK (unless you fit in piercing battle damage or other rank 4s that destroy cards). This deck also does not prevent attacks, so do not be afraid to keep your monsters in Attack Position to prevent any attempt the opponent makes to summon Divine Arsenal AA Zeus - Sky Thunder to wipe the field on your own turn (the opponent cannot attack directly with Zoodiac Boarbow, remember it is negated). Your monsters are huge, 3500 and 6000 (Dragonar ATK is doubled off of Utopia Double), your opponent will be very hard pressed to beat over them unless they play any kind of Honest. Another weakness this deck has is the chance that your opponent plays any form of quick-effect backrow removal, like Cosmic Cyclone or Twin Twisters. If they attempt to remove your PKRUM before their Main Phase, you cannot summon Kali Yuga, as PKRUM can only activate during the Main Phase. Use Numbers' Protection, which is searchable off Astraltopia, to stop their attempt. Alternatively, because Cosmic Cyclone sees plenty of play, you could play Artifact Lancea to prevent banishing for the turn, thereby protecting your PKRUM. Change the monster line up to be any of your favorite level 4s! Change the Extra Deck to help OTK after summoning Kali Yuga! Most of the cards are really cheap, the only expensive cards are Utopia Double itself, and the hand traps and Crossout Designator. Replace these to increase consistency or fill with your own jank. Thanks for reading! Remember to feel the flow and high-five the sky!

deck_excerpt: A relatively consistent Numerounius / Numeron deck.
deck_description:
Main strategy overview:

This deck focuses on keeping the field spell card "Numeron Network" on the field to summon 4 "Numeron" XYZ monsters that (depending on the circumstances) can be used to perform an OTK or to clear the monster zones. Occasionally, you may want to summon the bigger "Numerounius" XYZ monster by performing a combo that sends "Number C1: Numeron Chaos Gate Sunya" and "Numeron Network" to the Graveyard.   Here's a more in-depth explanation:

Strategy 1: Numeron OTK

To perform this strategy, you will have to start second. You will also probably have to have the most LP you can. Your opponent has to have some monsters with relatively low ATK (or DEF if they're in defense position) on the field. 1. Get "Numeron Network" in your field spell zone (you can use "Terraforming", "Numeron Wall", "Planet Pathfinder" or in the worst case scenario, "Metaverse"); 2. Activate "Numeron Network" and send a "Numeron Calling" to your GY, then summon the 4 "Numeron" XYZ monsters; 3. Attack your opponent's monsters with the 4 "Numeron" XYZ monsters, even if their ATK is lower than the opponent's monsters'. With the right circumstances, you should have inflicted about 8000 damage to your opponent, making you the winner.  

Strategy 2: Numerounius / Numerounius Numeronia

You may want to have "Swords of Revealing Light", "Mirror Force" (on your field) or "Battle Fader" (in your hand) before starting this strategy. 1. Get 1 "Numeron Network" in your field spell zone and another one (or two) in your hand (you can use "Terraforming", "Numeron Wall", "Planet Pathfinder" or in the worst case scenario, "Metaverse"), if you have "Number Wall" in your hand, set it; 2. Activate "Numeron Network" and send a "Numeron Calling" to your GY, then summon the 4 "Numeron" XYZ monsters; 3. XYZ summon "Number C1: Numeron Chaos Gate Sunya" from your extra deck using "Number 1: Numeron Gate Ekam" as material; 4. Assuming you have "Swords of Revealing Light", "Mirror Force" (on your field) or "Battle Fader" (in your hand) and "Number C1: Numeron Chaos Gate Sunya"'s effect wasn't negated, end your turn; 5. During your Standby Phase, activate "Number C1: Numeron Chaos Gate Sunya" to get it back on the field; 6. Activate the other copy of "Numeron Network" from your hand (make sure you still have a "Numeron Network" in your Field Spell zone); 7. Destroy "Number C1: Numeron Chaos Gate Sunya" using "Archfiend Eccentrick", "Unchained Twins - Aruha" or "Unchained Twins - Rakea"; 8. Activate "Numeron Network" and send "Numeron Chaos Ritual" to your GY; 9a. Via "Numeron Chaos Ritual"'s effect, XYZ summon "Number C1000: Numerounius"; 9b. Remember to activate "Number Wall" if you set it. Done! If Numerounius ever gets destroyed by an opponent's card effect and sent to the GY, you will be able to summon Numerounius Numeronia, which is basically a guaranteed win (if "Number Wall" is activated).  

General tips:

  • If somehow you end up in a situation where you can't use "Numeron Network", you can summon "Abominable Unchained Soul" by destroying "Unchained Twins - Aruha" or "Unchained Twins - Rakea" with another card effect;
  • If you haven't got "Number Wall" in your hand, you can also use "Numbers Protection".

deck_excerpt: Plunder Deck with Brave token engine
deck_description: The deck's pretty good, and really fun to play.

The main strat is getting out Melffy cards to summon Xyz monsters. The more powerful cards can be used to protect the Melffy cards long enough to Xyz summon. There are plenty of effect cards, as well as spell/trap cards that can serve this purpose, with a particular spotlight on graveyard retrieval and attack/effect negation. Plus, even if some kind of spell, trap, or monster defense can't be immediately set up, the Melffies can defend themselves for a bit. They can be called back to avoid damage, and the nature of their effects makes collecting a hand of Melffies easy, in addition to the regular draw.  This deck was assembled from cards I've come across card hunting. That is, except the Melffy cards which were purposefully sought out, and a few cards found in the Slifer deck.

This deck is mostly focused on damage, the name of the game is synchro summoning. The deck is mostly rock monster based, which makes getting out Adamancipator cards to synchro summon fairly easy. Several monsters can summon each other, and the ones that can't either have good damage output or defensive capabilities. I threw in the stardust dragon synchros for backup, and also because they're some of my favorite cards. With a couple tactical-field-wipes and an enemy controller thrown in, this deck makes for a strong contender, at least among me and my friends ^^;  I had to seek out a lot of these cards on tcg, but there are a few in there that are relatively common shuffling through cards at the local card shop.

Hi kids! Do you like violence drawing 10 cards a turn?  Well have I got the deck for you!  Remember Dragon Rulers using Super Rejuvenation to go +7 in the end phase because they were all dragons that had discard costs built in?  Like 75% of the Dragunity cards use a discard as cost. And you can play 10 Cards of Consonance targets. Which also adds a draw to your SR in end phase.  The optimal board for this deck is Spheres+Areadbhair+Dragunity Oubliette. You get there by using your discards to pack your graveyard full of Phalanx and Couse, then synchro summoning a Barcha and going off from the +3 that gives you.  It doesn't have the strongest boards but it compensates by loading your hand during the end phase, which is why the deck is 1/4 hand traps. Draw one or two and the negate (which banishes btw) and bounce should hold you through most combos, and Oubliette protects you against DRNM/Droplets.  The deck is also chock full of 1 1/2 and 2 card combos so added to the ease of getting to any of your monsters it's extremely consistent.
D/D/D cards and D/D work together, this deck will be a good one for you.

deck_excerpt: There's a light... in the distance... See it coming closer!
deck_description: Welcome back. Today we have a trap-based Dinorphia deck, where you burn yourself to near death stopping your opponent's plays, and then summoning your fusion monsters(preferably Rexstrum) on the field to control the game further and protect your LP. I also added a small dino engine in the side deck if you like that. As always, remember to like and tell me your qualms and concerns in the comments below, and have a good day. deck_excerpt: I love Ogdoadic and the Orcust engine has the most synergies with the deck.
deck_description: I love Ogdoadic, I know it will hardly become a meta unless a very powerful engine appears with absurd synergy with the deck because besides the problem of giving free resources to the opponent, you can't play with the deck alone because you don't have much to go go but the fact that the deck starters are proactive and start plays very easily and the engine follow up is very good. You redo your moves in a cyclic way and forcing interactions with the opponent. Besides how Snake Rain is an absurd card you always send a lot of Ogdoadic monster to the gy in the first game turn and so your deck arrives in turn 3 with 25 cards or less. which greatly improves the top deck of the engine used in conjunction with Ogdoadic. (Nauya + Any Normal Summon) and (Nunu + Any Random Card in Hand) already guarantee you by the 4 main engine names in circulation: Nunu, Nauya, Keurse and Aleirtt and thus the cycle can be redone in the next turn. A serious problem with the deck is the advantage it gives the opponent because there are monsters that have a floating effect when they leave the field to the gy or when they simply go to the gy, such as the Tri-Brigade Kitt and Nervall, among other examples such as the Destroyer Phoenix Destroyer. Enforcer that I happened to be able to send it to gy with the Dingirsu effect and when I used Keurse eff it brought the DPE back and that way the floating effect was alive again. As for Aleirtt, the situation is even more complicated because the opponent being able to add a monster to his hand is the worst condition a card could have since many times the card he adds back are hand traps like Nibiru, Ash Blossom and Veiler that will disturb you too much. That's why Ogdoabyss' best matchup is against Trap decks because they almost never have monsters in the gy so Keurse and Aleirtt's effects become free, but of course a card like Ice Dragon's Prison solves the problem for the opponent who is Another risk factor in the deck's gameplay: having Aleirtt banned virtually makes it impossible for your engine to continue recycling resources. Another problem with the Ogdoadic engine is the fact that you don't retain resources in the hand so as all monsters are in the gy you always find yourself at a card disadvantage in relation to the opponent during turns. About me not using Ogdoabyss in this build and its relationship with Water Lily: It is the best interaction that the Ogdoadic engine provides us but you will hardly summon it when tribute 3 monsters but with Water Lily and that's the big problem around the card, the fact that it is only viable if you use multiple copies of Water Lily and in the beginning when I tested the deck I used 3 copies because it is excellent in the grind game. Then I saw that the deck needed more consistency and I cut it down to 2 copies and finally I realized that Water Lily doesn't improve any play of the Ogdoabyss engine if you try to use it as a Starter along with Nauya or Nunu then it is a card that just is good when you have at least 4 Reptiles in GY or have already accessed King of the Feral Imps and Keurse Summon Nauya plays so it doesn't make your engine come out of inertia unless you have already activated other Ogdoabyss cards and therefore lower it for 1 copy was excellent for maintaining deck consistency. I say that using multiple copies of Water Lily is only good if you are using the pure version of the deck. What brought me the most doubts about this build is the use of Amunessia or Aron, the Ogdoadic and their speech as follows: Aron has an interaction effect that's easier to resolve than Amunessia's because the simplest thing to happen is for the opponent to add a card to their hand and it even manages to be better than Dark Law because it doesn't need to be added from the deck but of the GY as for example he trigger eff if the opponent uses the effect of Eldlich, the Golden Lord of summon because no one remembers but first he adds himself to the hand and then enters the field. This effect is so good that your opponent will think twice before leaving adding cards to the hand for fear of losing an important card. Amunessia's interaction effect is more powerful than Aron's but it's much easier to play around it and we don't have many decks in this format that need to summon gy monsters at the beginning of their moves before dealing with the Amunessia. The cool thing about this effect is that it combo with Keurse because the opponent can summon from a gy monster when Keurse enters the field (by the effect itself) so this is a way to try to force the Amunessia effect to happen but still the opponent can simply choose not to summon the GY. Now what made me opt for Amunessia is the use of the second effect of the cards because Aron brings the advantage over Amunesia of being able to add any Ogdoadic to the hand that already pays the Knightmare Unicorn cost at the same time you decrease the number. of bad draws in the deck having a better top deck. But the fact that Amunessia gives GY summon easily is very relevant if you want to avoid the worst part of Ogdoadic Keurse monsters and especially Aleirtt from giving free resources to the opponent and this is relevant from the point of view of having a consistent way to access Aleirtt without the opponent being able to add a monster back to the hand at the same time you return two banned monsters and can very potentially return Orcust Knightmare to the GY for example is something that is priceless. As you don't use Ogdoabyss, the monster you bring won't generate interaction but it already guarantees access to cards like Zeroboros in the opponent's turn with I:P Masquerena. Another very good factor of Amunesia is the simple fact that it is a DARK attribute which is relevant if you want to summon it at the end of your play with Water Lily, unlike Aron, which cannot because of the restriction of Orcust monsters. I believe that Amunessia proved to be the best option to use in conjunction with Orcust. What I find most interesting about Orcust is the fact that the gameplay is very intelligent and I think it is one of the decks that most represent modern yugioh in the way of being cyclical and never running out of gas and having effective interactions with the opponent. I don't really miss Harp Horror and with it the deck won't improve to the point of becoming a meta again, but it will be the ideal way to use having access to Knightmare and Skeleton in the GY since the World Wand doesn't allow you this combination but the Harp Horror does. The fact that Harp Horror is Level 4 is also very good for this version of the deck using the Ogdoadic engine because it improves the mix of moves using Nunu and Nauya and the deck would have more consistency and power. Regarding Orcust card ratios at the beginning I used 3 Knightmare and 2 Skeleton and 1 Crescendo but after testing a lot and doing probabilities I came to the conclusion that at first I never want to see 2 Knightmare in my starting hand so I only use 2 copies for decrease this chance and I also realized that whenever I opened with Skeleton in my hand, he was essentially the worst draw among the initial 5 cards, that is, he bricks my hand every time I see him and Crescendo has the conflict that I don't being able to use the Ogdoadic engine in the turn that activates its Search effect which is too costly since the Ogdoadic engine is very important in the functioning of the deck but I confess that in grind game matches I missed setting Crescendo with the Galatea. If you find consistency it's something I'm looking for a lot with this deck so much that I've added Danger! Mothman! which is the best Danger! to use in this deck because it is Level 4, which greatly improves Ogdoadic plays and its effect when discarded has a lot of synergy with Orcust and Ogdoadic cards and it's not crazy to use it because you already have the problem of giving free resources to the opponent with Keurse and Aleirtt so it won't be Mothman! the only villain in history to give the opponent an advantage. In Extra Deck I have comments to make about the use of Exciton Knight, AA-Zeus, Sanaphond, Lambda: these 4 cards are used to improve the playing options of the Ogdoadic engine because thanks to Zohah it is very easy in the Grind Game to start the turn doing Exciton Knight to force interactions from the opponent besides after using the effect you go to battle phase and do AA-Zeus in Main Phase 2 and force one more interaction. Sanaphond is a counter to the deck's own two engines and you won't be able to use any Orcurst effects on your opponent's turn when doing so but I consider it the best generic RANK-8 option to do with the Ogdoadic engine because it puts a lot of pressure on the field with an absurd atk/def stat that cannot be destroyed by effects. Lambda is very good so you guarantee you have live Gamma in your hand turn 1 and you can return the Driver to GY with Aleirtt so even if you use Gamma and it gets banned in the End Phase with Driver and Lambda trigger eff to add another Gamma from your deck you simply use Aleirtt's effect and let the Gamma live again to protect you from hand traps or interrupt the opponent. About the use of 2 Dingirsu it turns out that you don't necessarily access the second Dingirsu with the Orcust engine but Ogdoadic does this role of the use of the second copy. Regarding Longirsu I have to say that the LINK-3 is the worst LINK rating there is unless you are a potencial LINK-4 by nature like Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians but Longirsu when you can do it he proves to be the difference between losing and winning games. A detail about the combos I was at the beginning testing with Ogdoabyss instead of Amunessia when I made the tutorials so it turns out that you are supposed to use Water Lily in the beginning before using Orcust monster effects so as I now use Amunessia it's much better to save to use Water Lily at the end of the combo. In some combos I don't even use Water Lily because I don't have 4 Reptiles with different names in the GY before I need to use the effects of Orcust monsters but that only happens if you want to summon from Ogdoabyss, at the end of the combo it's practically always possible to use the Water Lily to give Summon of Amunessia which is something I want to emphasize about tutoring. Combo Tutorial: Place the URL continuation on the duelingbook site after .com/ /////////////////////////////Combos with the engines separately: Combo 1: Nunu + (Reptile Monster) Gamestate: LINK-2 Lambda/I:P + Amunessia replay?id=813757-35351661 Combo 1. 1: Nunu + Any Random Card replay?id=813757-35438465 Combo 2: Snake Rain + Discard Previously Gamestate: LINK-2 + Amunessia replay?id=813757-35352213 Combo 3: Nauya + Any Normal Summon Gamestate: Number 68 /in GY: all the 4 best Ogdoadic Names replay?id=813757-35438310 Combo 4: Girsu Gamestate: I:P + Babel /in GY: Dingirsu + Galatea + Knightmare + Girsu replay?id=813757-35376499 /////////////////////////////Synergy between Ogdoadic Orcust engines: Combo 1: Snake Rain + Knightmare Gamestate: I:P + Amunessia + Babel /in GY: Galatea + Dingirsu + Knightmare replay?id=813757-35352461 Combo 2: (Snake Rain + Knightmare) + Girsu Gamestate: I:P + (***Keurse if you use Skeleton eff) + Babel + Amunessia /in Hand: Water Lily(if not used this turn) + (Zohah or Nauya) /in GY: Galatea + Dingirsu + Knightmare + Skeleton replay?id=813757-35368062 Combo 2. 1: (Snake Rain + Discard) + Girsu (ROUTE King of Feral Imps) Gamestate: I:P + Amunessia + Babel /in GY: Galatea + Dingirsu + Knightmare + All Ogdoadic names replay?id=813757-35376575 Combo 3: Girsu + Nunu (Skeleton ROUTE/Can also do through the World Wand) Gamestate: I:P + Amunessia + Dingirsu(Skeleton as Material) + Babel /in Hand: Nothing /in GY: Girsu replay?id=813757-35368507 Combo 3. 1: Girsu + Nunu (SAFE ROUTE - not so dependent on Girsu's effects) Gamestate: I:P + Babel + Amunessia /in GY: Dingirsu + Knightmare + Galatea replay?id=813757-35369172 ^^Version using World Wand Gamestate: I:P + Babel + Amunessia /in GY: Dingirsu + Knightmare + Galatea replay?id=813757-35443342 ^^Version using Skeleton - more efficient way to do this combo but it needs to use Aleirtt's effect and can give resources to the opponent Combo 4: Nunu + (any Random Card) or [anyLevel4 like Zohah] + Knightmare BANISHED Gamestate: I:P + Dingirsu + Babel /in GY: Knightmare replay?id=813757-35369709 Combo 5: Nunu + Knightmare (Skeleton ROTA is the most efficient but not the safest) Gamestate: I:P Masquerena + Dingirsu + Babel /in GY: Knightmare replay?id=813757-35442672 Combo 6: Girsu + Nauya Gamestate: I:P Masquerena + Amunessia + Babel /in GY: Dingirsu + Knightmare + Galatea replay?id=813757-35437578 Comments of a gameplay on the deck: You get a lot of value by using Aleirtt and return Knightmare to GY after sending Skeleton to GY (Aleirtt will be Amunessia's last summon by the DARK lock) Skeleton Reborn Knightmare and go to Galatea to shuffle Skeleton and Set Babel and make Dingirsu. A cool play to watch is Skeleton Reborn Girsu, and Girsu send Knightmare and Knightmare send Gizmek Orochi or World Wand to summon Skeleton back LINK-2 Galatea and eff Shuffle World Wand and set Babel and make Dingirsu to attach Knightmare and make I:P Masquerena or ANOTHER Galatea Opponent's turn: Skeleton Reborn Dingirsu and eff to Send and Galatea Shuffle Skeleton set Return or Crescendo Even if Babel is sent to GY whoever is your Draw for Turn you can set Babel again. This synergy also applies with Zohah which is why I use Exciton Knight because you can always return Zohah to hand and Normal Summon and use Nunu eff and Tribute to Keurse that brings Nauya and that way you can do it the Exciton Knight in the grind game. Gizmek Orochi eff and Knightmare target Orochi send Skeleton and Skeleton eff Reborn Dingirsu and Dingirsu Attach Skeleton Some technical play from the deck: Nunu te lock in Special Summon from Reptile monster and you usually get out of lock by doing RANK-4 Feral Imps or tributing it to Keurse for example. Forgetting this restriction costs games. Water Lily only Special Summons if you have 5 Reptiles with DIFFERENT NAMES in the GY and not if you have 5 Reptiles including repeat copies. Girsu, can only create a token on each side of the field if you don't control other monsters. Speaking of lock you on something, all Orcust cards lock you on Dark after using its effects so basically you should always summon from Nunu and Keurse before using the Orcust engine. Gizmek Orochi can only use 1 of the effects per turn, so if you want to get the most out of it you must summon it in the End Phase of your opponent's turn to be able to use the pop effect on your turn. It is not uncommon for you to LINK-4 with this deck using 4 monsters as material because Ogdoadic cards are very good at putting 2-3 monsters on the field and unless you have a Galatea or Longirsu on the field the Orcust engine will only Give you monsters that count as Link Rating 1. A problem with this deck is the fact that when you're locked in Dark there aren't good LINK-2 options available so you end up having to do it using multiple monsters to access a LINK- 3 or LINK-4 in place. Overall I think the deck is far from competitive even more with so much unfair in this format where all decks either use a Floodgate that says "You won't play yugioh" or use Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer (DPE) which is a card very difficult to deal with this deck unless the opponent leaves it on the field to be sent to gy with Dingirsu which wins games alone for no reason. For sure after the next banlist this deck will be better to play at least until the arrival of Brave Token which is essentially a new engine to be abused on the same level as DPE bringing many problems to the format and making yugioh less and less fun.

deck_excerpt: Tri-Brigade Melffy, with a heavy serving of Melffy. This deck tries to play a longer game than most Tri-Brigade decks, and focuses on recurring resour
deck_description: This deck is built to play a longer version of the game than most Tri-Brigade decks. This is a bit off the beaten path, and any advice or insight you might have I am open to.  The deck's main goals are two-fold: use the Tri-Brigade monsters to get out their bosses and create card advantage, and use the Melffy engine to remove opponents cards and negate their effects. I won't go over the Tri-Brigade strategy here because I believe most other Tri-Brigade deck-lists have it covered better than I could. The Melffy engine is similar to most others you will see: use Puppy to pull out Kalantosa who then pops a card. We are Tri-ing (sorry) something a bit different by including Melffy Pony and Melffy Fenny. Pony can put Kalantosa back in hand from the GY, and Fenny can summon a Kalantosa from hand (useful if we hard-draw it or recurse it with pony).  We also included the Hop Ear Squadron and Valerifawn, both of which are tuners. We can use those to make Herald of the Arc Light for a negate, or Jiujiu for staying power (it is very easy to get 2 monsters with the same type and attribute in our GY). The only other real departure for our deck from the norm is two copies of Pot of Avarice. Since we want to play a drawn out game, this card helps control our GY, returning any Melffys sent there and recursing our link monsters.  Thank you for taking the time to read this, I hope you like my deck!

In a turn after you then summon Five-Headed Link Dragon in the zone next to Binary using Tri-Gate and two other monsters, and bring back Trigate Wizard using Transcode's effect. Finally, on your next turn, you Fusion summon Cyberse Clock Dragon using Tri-Gate and Five Headed Link Dragon and put him where Five Headed Link Dragon was. Then bring Tri-Gate back from the graveyard. It takes a long time to complete, and will usually be stopped before then, but when you do get it out it's near impossible to beat. This deck wasn't my idea, my friend created it, but my deck uses some different cards than his.

deck_excerpt: One shot your opponent in a way they won't normally expect. By milling their entire deck into the banish zone and sometimes nuke their life points wit
deck_description:
Main Objective Use Inferno Tempest successfully in your turn. Win Condition(s)
  • Decking out your opponent
  • Reduce their LP to 0
Requirements to pull of combo: Hand Requirement
  • Any Kaiju monster or Spell
  • Any 0ATK monster
  • 1 copy of Inferno Tempest
  • 1 copy of Dynamite (Optional: but does increase winrate)
Board Requirement
  • 1 monster on opponent's field or your field (if you have the Kaiju spell in your hand)
  • Have 3400 or more LP (between 3100 and 3400 the combo gets more difficult to pull off)
Combo Step 1: Access the board, read for any big monster that can negate traps/spells or destroy/remove your monsters. Step 2: Get rid of any tricky monsters found in step 1, by summoning a kaiju in Attack mode over them. Step 3: Summon your 0ATK monster Step 4: Attack the Kaiju monster with your 0ATK monster. You should take about 3000 damage. Step 5: Play Inferno Tempest (Preferably in a zone where there are no traps on your opponents side, because infinite impertinence exist) Note: This will trigger the effects of Necroface and banish an additional 15 cards Step 6: Set the copy of  Dynamite (optional) Step 7: End your turn Step  8: Activate  Dynamite (optional) You win NOTE: Conditions to pull off aren't easy, after testing deck for 3 weeks winrate has been about 50%. Major problems with deck:
  • Deck is not very Consistent
  • You don't want a Necroface in your hand or field, but you do need 3 copies in your deck for this combo to work
  • Difficulty getting Inferno Tempest, beta version of this deck has included Left Arm Offering which does work, but could also end up making your hand more dead as well. Might reintroduce that card, to see if I can improve consistency.

deck_excerpt: Invoked Utopia, very competitive budget version, even 2-3 negates can't stop this deck, price should be for the whole deck around 200 dolars. Go again
deck_description: I was playing before invoked dogmatika dpe/shaddol and i can say Utopia Invoked is much stronger and the price is much cheaper. Utopia Invoked can keep playing even if the opponent use 2 - 3 negates thanks to Armed/Ascended sage because u can chain with utopia double the same turn. The purpose of Kaiju is as board breaker and light target for Invoked engine and Small World. This deck doesn't need Artemis or Almiraj - Gardna for invoked engine.  Magical Mallet is the replacement of pot of prosperity. The most important turn in duel is your first turn, doesn't matter if u going first or second, your first turn is important, u can draw up to 4 new cards if u going first and up to 5 cards if u going second, thanks to magical mallet, much better card for this deck than upstart goblin and pot of desire. also, if u have a brick (pegasus, double or nothing etc) in your hand u can shoufle them back in deck, same as zexal construct.  Small World can be easily used, just banish 1 light monster from your hand, reveal Effect Veiller from the deck and add 1 Aleister, Armed/Ascended sage, Astral Kuriboh or Kaiju to you hand. Basicaly u have acess to every monster in your deck except tornado and bancho, thanks to small world and Effect Veiller. Small world most of the time will be used when you have in your hand (Onomatopaira + Aleister/Meltdown), (Aleister + Aleister) , (Extender + Extender) and/or + kaiju  Always u will want in your hand 1 starter and 1 extender, in that way even if your opponent use 2-3 negates u can still keep playing. Starters (14 cards), chance to open going first 90%: onomatopaira, onomatopickup, meltdown, Aleister (+ small world) Extenders (13), chance to open going first 88%: Astral Kuriboh, Armed/Ascended sage (+ searchers Zexal construct, reinforcement, small world) Board Breakers , chance to open going second 71%: kaiju Consistency (2): Magical Mallet (thanks to it the chance to open starter is increasing to 93% , extender 91% and board breaker 74%)  bricks (2): double or nothing and pegasus (hyper rank, tornado and invocation is considered bad draw but they still can be used) solutions: -If u draw double or nothing u can go directly with Ascended sage to number 39 ,after c39 ,dragner and etc. With Armed sage instead go to number 41 in defense or go to number 39 - c39 - utopia lightning +tornado. -If u draw pegasus, use Ascended sage for utopia double - number 39 - c39 - dragner - number 22/90 and in the opponent turn u can summon number 41 in defense after u resolved all your effects. -If u draw tornado or hyper rank up magic, is not big deal because they can be used from the hand, just keep in mind to use Armed Sage for utopia double and (if the opponent use negate eff or not) then add pegasus in hand and chain with utopia double- summon dragonic and equip tornado to him, after use the eff of dragonic to equip pegasus from your hand.  the deck is good going second and first. if u play competetive, then u will see a lot of swordsoul and birds users. tips: if u going against swordsoul then go second and use more monster negate (number 90) instead omni negate (number 22), if u go against birds then go first.  This is my first day testing the budget version, it can go against any meta deck and i can go in tournament with this deck because is not expensive. Invoked dogmatika dpe/shaddol was my previous deck, it is strong, however, Invoked Utopia is much stronger and cheaper. Around 200 dolars should be the price for the whole deck including side deck.  Hand traps lovers, this deck doesn't have space for hand traps, however, hand traps is to interrupt and prevent board to be established but board breakers can destroy already established board. One deck to run hand traps there must be at least 10 - 12 free spaces for them because u can't prevent board to be established just with veiller / impermamence, u must use more than 1 hand trap to do that (except if u are lucky and draw nibiro), but for the board breakers 6-7 cards is perfectly fine because u need 1 card to destroy already established board. So don't replace kaiju for example with hand traps or dark ruler or whatever, everything in the main deck have purpose.  probably i will update the side deck and extra deck in future, but for now is ok Video with few duels from the 1st day testing:  https://youtu.be/g9jnnbiO-no

deck_excerpt: Megaliths with Advanced Ritual Art - Post Common Charity Cup 2
deck_description:
MEGALITH A Rock Solid Ritual Deck. Megalith has been a deck I've enjoyed ever since it came out in Ignition Assault around the time I started playing Yu-Gi-Oh!. It's a ritual combo deck that abuses the non-hard once per turn on ritual summon effects of their level-4 ritual monsters to gain advantage, and their ability to use those monsters to ritual summon more Megalith monsters or any other ritual monsters. This combined with the fact that they are rock monsters and thus could use Gallant Granite to search, the Adamancipator monsters as tuner extenders for Crystron Halqifibrax, and Block Dragon as a repeatable +3 allowed the deck to see niche high-level play during 2020. The archetype was also released on Duel Links in Chronicle of Glory in July 2020 and would see niche play there too especially after the release of Xyz monsters to that game as a deck that could repeatedly destroy 2-6 cards with Megalith Bethor, then attack for large amounts of damage using Megalith Phaleg's boost and could search cards like Cyber Angel Dakini as an out to Invoked Cocytus or make use of a toolbox of Rank-4 and Rank-8 Xyz monsters. In Common Charity then deck functions similar to the Duel Links version in some regards, the deck is built to repeatedly destroy the opponents' cards with Bethor, gaining advantage through the deck's field spell, Megalith Portal, and continuous trap, Megalith Emergence, it has access to a toolbox of Rank-4 and Rank-8 Xyz monsters like Time Thief Redoer, Tornado Dragon, or Number 62: Galaxy-Eyes Prime Photon Dragon and it can deal with opposing strategies through searchable cards like Cyber Angel Dakini, Amorphactor Pain, or Artifact Lancea, but it also has access to some of the most powerful set-up pieces of the archetype, Megalith Unformed, which allows you to ritual summon from the deck by tributing twice that monsters level, and Megalith Phul, a level-2 ritual monster that on ritual summon adds a ritual monster from your GY and becomes that monsters level and can ritual summon Megalith monsters from the deck by tributing monsters from hand or field during both players' main phases. Additionally, the deck plays well into some of the more common removal in the format - Kaijus. Most of the boards the deck makes lose very little to a Kaiju, you can still pop 2-4 on your opponent's main phase using Bethor's effect if you bring back Phul using Emergence, and you can use the Kaiju as ritual material, Jizikiru and Dogoran can be the entire requirement for summoning a level-8 Megalith using Phul or the level-8s, the level-4 monsters can use themselves and a Raidan in order to summon a high-level ritual monster, and Dogaran specifically can be used as the entire requirement to summon a level-4 monster off of Unformed or be overlayed with another level-8 to make one of the deck's rank-8 monsters. 2-Card Combos This Version of Megalith is built around having multliple two-card combos that set up Phul + Portal + Emergance. There are 2 main ways the deck facilitates this Unformed and Advanced Ritual Art. Each of these two card combos can be expanded upon in different ways depending on the other cards in your hand, and most combos that don't start with a piece tend to do similar things just with a higher investment. Unformed + Senju/Manju:
  1. Normal summon Senju of the Thousand Hands or Manju of the Ten Thousand Hands, use their effect to add Megalith Och.
  2. Activate Megalith Unformed tributing Och in order to summon Megalith Phul. Phul adds Och back to hand becoming a level 4 in the process.
  3. Tribute the Senju/Manju in order to summon Megalith Hagith from the deck, Hagith's effect adds Megalith Portal.
  4. Activate Megalith Portal, then activate Hagith's effect in order to ritual summon Och from hand using itself as material, this proccs Portal which adds back the Hagith. You can also activate Och to draw a card, and then discard a card.
  5. Activate Och's effect to ritual summon the Hagith from hand. Activate Hagith's effect again to search Megalith Emergence. Set Emergence.
  6. You now have 2 level-4 monsters on field - Hagith and Phul, Portal and Emergence, and 1 Ritual Monster name already in the GY. You can overlay the two monsters for a rank-4 or keep them around as ritual material or allow you to play through removal on Emergence depending on the situation.
Advanced Ritual Art + Senju/Manju:
  1. Normal summon Senju/Manju, use their effect to add Megalith Hagith.
  2. Activate Advanced Ritual Art to ritual summon Hagith by sending a level 4 normal monster from your deck like Dunames Dark Witch. Hagith effect adds Unformed.
  3. Activate Unformed tribute the Hagith for Phul. Phul adds back the Hagith and becomes level-4.
  4. Phul effect tribute the Senju/Manju for a Hagith from deck. Hagith adds Portal.
  5. Activate Portal. Use the Hagith to ritual summon on field to ritual summon the Hagith in hand. Hagith adds Emergence. Portal can add the Hagith in GY to hand.
  6. You're in a similar position to the first combo except you a second Hagith in rotation rather than an Och, and you've used the garnet in the deck. This can be worse in certain situations where you want to revive Och with Emergence to ritual summon a non-Megalith Ritual Monster during your opponent's main phase.
Hagith + Manju:
  1. Normal summon Manju, add Advanced Ritual Art
  2. Step-2 on from combo 2.
Apart form the Megalith cards and cards mentioned in combos there are a bunch of cards that can be played in this deck in the main, side, or extra deck that have specific applications in this deck compared to others
  • Cyber Angel Benten is a level-6 ritual monster that when tributed can add a Light Fairy monster from your deck to your hand, such as Manju or Senju. This effect is not once per turn and could search itself leading it to be limited because of its interactions with Drytron monsters in advanced. It also has an on field effect that never comes up which is that it does burn when it destroys a monster by battle equal to that monsters defence.
  • Cyber Angel Dakini is a level-8 Light Fairy ritual monster that makes the opponent send one of their monsters to the GY, this is non-destructive, non-targeting, non-effecting removal, which means it can out a boss with any protection if your opponent does not have any other monsters on field. This gives the deck a searchable out to Gouki The Powerload Ogre or Lunalight Leo Dancer among other problematic bosses. It also gives your ritual monsters piercing and can return a ritual monster from your GY to your hand during your end phase.
  • Cyber Angel Vrash is a level-10 Light Fairy ritual monster that on summon destroys all monsters your opponent controls that were special summoned from the Extra Deck and burn for 1000 for each and attack twice that turn. It also has a Stardust Dragon effect by shuffling a ritual monster from your GY into your deck. If there were less indestructible Extra Deck monsters around I might run this. Being a level-10 changes the ritual maths a little - you can't tribute 2 level-4s, but you can tribute a level-4 and a level-6 or higher monster.
  • Artifact Lancea is a level-5 Light Fairy non-ritual effect monster that can be tributed from hand or field during your opponent's turn to stop players from banishing cards. It is a searchable way to deal with Tenyi's follow up for a turn, which is normally long enough to turn the tide such that you can establish control of the game.
  • Demise, Agent of Armageddon is level-4 ritual monster that is a non-targeting pop when ritual summoned and if it is sent to the GY, you can target one of your ritual monsters then while that monster is on the field your opponent can't respond to any of your ritual monsters effects - even ones in the GY.
  • Amorphactor Pain is a level-8 ritual monster that after it is summoned your opponent skips their next Main Phase 1 (Which at time of writing is bugged on EDO Pro) and negates the effects of face-up Fusion, Synchro, or Xyz Monsters on the field. This can shut down Lunalight as their main forms of interaction are through Xyz and Fusion monsters and the effect to skip their main phase 1 also allows you to effectively Threatning Roar them on subsequent turns when you have dealt with their current field.
  • Lord of the Red is a level-8 ritual monster that can destroy 1 target spell/trap and 1 target monster per turn each when a card or effect is activated. This is a decent Pre-Preparation of Rites target that allows you to potentially destroy 2 cards per turn, however the deck already has an in archetype way of destroying even more cards every turn.
  • Transonic Bird is a level-4 ritual monster that can send a ritual spell from the deck during your opponent's turn to copy its effect, it's ritual spell Sonic Tracker makes the Bird's level equal the level of its material and can be banished from the GY to target a ritual monster then send a monster with the same type or attribute from the deck to the GY. This enables a 3 card way to resolve Amorphactor Pain before your opponent's next main phase and can set up additional names and target in the GY for your Megaliths, however this is pretty gimmicky, requires more bricks in the form of Earth Chant, and the other effects of Transonic Bird don't synergise with any of the other ritual monsters the deck runs.
  • Trade In is a spell that can discard a level-8 monster in order to draw 2 cards. This deck is playing a reasonably high number of level-8 monsters already, so this card could give the deck more consistency, however it can still be dead and when it is, it's only use is to be discarded with Och. I would like to test this card out in the Future.

So, I wanted to play Mekk-Knight, but I also wanted to play Orcust, and just so ahppened to wanna play Crusadia, So we play all 3 at the same time. kinda. Game 1 we play Mekk-Knight Orcust, pretty fun and basic Mekk-Knight stuff with some Orcust combos on the side after youv'e made your Mekk plays thanks to Girsu. Game 2 we side out ALL the Orcust cards. This includes; World Wand, Knightmare, 2x GIrsu, Skele, Bombard, Crescendo, Return, Instant Fusion, Card Destruction, Winda, Dingirsu, Galatea. And we put in all the Crusadia cards. Mekk-Crusadia is also pretty swell, basic Mekk-Knight stuff, with the capability to OTK thanks to the Crusadia cards. Instant Fusion + Winda is actually very good for reasons other than Dingirsu, can use her for Link 2 material, bring her back with Succ for some bullying, but can also bring her back with Secrets as it grabs any level 5+ monster. Something very obvious but I figured it's worth mentioning anyway. Some notes, Card Destruction is there because I needed a 15th card to side out and I thought it would be fun and dumb to include in the list, could probably find something more useful to have there like, literally any 1 off. Clara & Rushika is there for if you've bricked going second with only an Orcust normal summon and Mekk-Knights in hand, can use it in MP2 to make Mekk plays, not a good card should probably run Linkuriboh for the Girsu token but Linkuriboh isn't cute girls so it didn't make the cut Also, the deck has next to no goign first plays. Unless you open Girsu or a Crusadia monster, you have 0 going first cards.

deck_excerpt: A simple go-second deck focused on quickly fusion summoning Evil HEROs with Masked HEROs as a back-up option. Also includes a few generic budget cards
deck_description:
Price based on ygoprodeck.com's TCGPlayer estimated USD price on January 9th, 2022.
Deck Overview: A simple go-second deck focused on quickly fusion summoning Evil HEROs with Masked HEROs as a back-up option. Also includes a few generic budget cards to boost the overall power level of the deck. Game Strategy: Can reliably summon an Evil HERO fusion in one turn, and all HEROs in the deck can be used as Mask Change targets. If two HEROs are on the field, can Link Summon Xtra HERO Infernal Devicer to search fusion materials from the deck while also increasing the attack of Evil HEROs it points to. A Hero Lives can summon Elemental HERO Shadow Mist to search Mask Change in a single turn. Supreme King's Castle can be used to boost the attack of an Evil HERO in battle against another monster - and can send the Evil HERO Dark Gaia in the Extra Deck to increase by 1600 ATK. Raigeki and Red Reboot are generic cards to improve power level when going second, while the three Solemn Warning are generic cards to improve power level when going first instead. Budget Upgrades: Obvious picks would be going for Evil HERO Malicious Bane, Evil HERO Adusted Gold, and Evil HERO Sinister Necrom to boost the overall power level and consistency of the deck. E -Emergency Call can also improve the deck's consistency. Can also go for extra copies of Keeper of Dragon Magic, Elemental HERO Prisma, and Elemental HERO Shadow Mist.

deck_excerpt: An actually good pure DDD without halq.
deck_description: This deck, even though it has a lot of one ofs that you would call "bricks", it is actually extremely consistent and can fully utilize all of those "bricks" even if you draw them. Typically, your end boards consist of caeser (2 solemn warnings), makina with a dark contract on the field (a weird kind of hope harbinger for monsters that doesnt negate), siegfreid (hot red dragon archfiend abyss for spells and traps) and dark contract with the eternal darkness (continuous trap that locks the opponent from tributing for a tribute summon (flunderezze), fusing monsters from the field or using monsters for a synchro or xyz materials. It also provides nifty protection. It can usually do this around nib (berfomet change a dd to lvl six overlay with lil gengis and make caeser) and can play around dark ruler (hint: respond to dark ruler with eternal darkness then chain siegfried negate). It can play through a through  disruptions, but not a fully established board (in most cases). Thats why we have a side deck. It is a fun, semi-competitive, reasonably budget but pretty damn hard to play deck. The combo lines vary a lot and it can take a bit of thinking to find the ideal route. Have fun!
