deck_excerpt: Cyber Dragons, specifically tailored for Common Charity. Hit with BIG NUMBER and OTK!
deck_description: A deck specifically made for the "Common Charity" format that is officially supported by Konami. This format only uses cards that come in the common rarity. Here is a bit of a simpler deck explanation as opposed to my 2000 word+ articles. I'm gonna pump out quite a bit of Common Charity guides in the near future for the sake of this young and exciting format! This list is an almost identical list of the Duelist Bombderday who achieved a top 8 in the "Common Charity 2" out of 64 players. Forced to only use common cards, Cyber Dragon loses key combo pieces like Galaxy Soldier and Cyber Herz. Not only that, Cyber Dragon loses its main boss monster, Cyber Dragon Infinity. With It's signature control card out of the format, Cyber Dragons only have one option - HIT WITH BIG NUMBER. This deck aims to go second, opting to completely obliterate the opponent's lifepoints after breaking their board/backrow. Currently the meta in Common Charity consists of a lot of potent backrow like Solemns, Torrential Tribute, Compulse, etc. so x3 Hey! Trunade serves as this deck's backrow removal. Chimeratech Rampage Dragon also destroys backrow with it's on-summon ability. Monster board breakers in this deck consist of  Jizukiru (searcheable off of Cyber Repair Plant) and x3 Forbidden Chalice. Combos with this deck are hand dependent, simple and straightforward, but the goal is always the same - summon lots of Cyber Dragons after breaking your opponent's board and OTK. Hands with Cyber Emergency/Cyber Dragon Core + Machine Duplication are essentially full combo. The Extra Deck features the standard Cyber Dragon monsters, except without Infinity. The only unusual monster is Barbaroid, the Ultimate Battle Machine, which is summonable if your Cyber Dragon Nova gets sent to the GY. This deck doesn't really do well in a grindgame, so make sure to destroy your opponent's lifepoints quickly and efficiently before they bounce back and force you in a unpleasant losing situation. Common Charity is a breathe of fresh air in the face of Yugioh's often stale meta, I encourage duelists to try it out! It's honestly the most fun I've had in Yugioh in a while!

deck_excerpt: Force out a grindgame with Superdreadnought Super Dora and win in a battle of attrition with Fortress - all backed by an arsenal of purple cards!
deck_description:
A deck specifically made for the "Common Charity" format that is officially supported by Konami. This format only uses cards that come in the common rarity.
Here is a bit of a simpler deck explanation as opposed to my 2000 word+ articles. I'm gonna pump out quite a bit of Common Charity guides in the near future for the sake of this young and exciting format! Inspired by the surprisingly successful Trap Machina list that topped PAK's LCS Tourney, Machina Train Control copies that strategy, geared for Common Charity! Losing the resource/boardwipe loop that Machina is famous (Machina Citadel) and its primary searcher (Machina Redeployment) this deck is focused lesser on a Machina strategy but more towards trains. Control the board with Traps and Trains, and grind your opponent out in a resource war! Designed to turbo out its nigh invincible boss monster Number 81, Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora, the strategy of this deck is a "protect the castle" strategy - Sit on a unaffected high attack monster while backed with trap cards. Even if Super Dora is taken out, this deck easily can make it again, especially with access to its fieldspell, Revolving Switchyard. The traps used in this deck feature some of the most ridiculous floodgates in the game, completely shutting down opponent's plays while your plays are unhindered. Gozen Match shuts down most "meta" Common Charity decks like Tenyi and Lunalight. Imperial Order and Anti-Spell Fragrance prevent spell cards from being used. Machina Overdrive turns any machine into Machina Fortress, a strong boss monster on its own right. Since this deck features many high level machine monsters, Fortress is easily summonable from the hand or GY. Gearframe and Unclaspare also give access to Fortress, since they both foolish burial Fortress to the GY. In the grindgame, Fortress almost always trades more often in your favour, due to it's effects when destroyed by battle or targeted by card effect. In the grind game, Time Thief Redoer is KING in Common Charity, and he can be made easily with Machine Gearframe + Machine Unclaspare. Other rank 4 options are available, depending on the situation. The trap cards Crackdown, Torrential Tribute, Judgment and Strike are chosen since they are the highest impact cards that trade positively for the player using them. Torrential Tribute can be used without destroying Super Dora since it can be chained with it's own effect to be immune to Torrential's fieldwipe. Overall, the gameplan of this deck is to force out a grindgame with a towers monster (Super Dora) and win in a battle of attrition with Fortress. All of this is accomplished with oppressive floodgates which block your opponent's play, while methodically picking them apart with high impact trap cards. Common Charity is a breathe of fresh air in the face of Yugioh's often stale meta, I encourage duelists to try it out! It's honestly the most fun I've had in Yugioh in a while!

deck_description: Fun monster cards to play with

Summon froggies and paleo's to get the lord of YOINKS Toadally Awesome on the field ASAP you can always replace the Marincess Coral Anemone for a second Divine Arsenal-AA Sus - Sky Thunder if you prefer that. The deck has a lot of search power with Traptrick so I like running 2 off some traps to get extra versatility in my duels. I side Imperial Order because most of the times if I don't get it in my starting hand I usually accidently drop it in GY using Needlebug Nest. (and i dislike that card let's all hope it get's banned)

Fury of Kairyu-Shin has such a nice synergy with this deck not only does it get you a Torrential Tribute it's GY effect also protects your froggies and Paleo's against card effects AKA wipe the field with Torrential Tribute while you keep all your water monsters.

I know this deck probably isn't the best version but it's how I like to play this deck. You can always change some stuff of course. This is one of my favorite deck's atm and if you haven't tried it before.. you should! It's also possible to make the deck more budget.
